.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_11\_codex_stdout.txt:146:   17: Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved tirzepatide under the proprietary name Mounjaro on May 15, 2022, as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus.[17] The FDA-approved dosing regimen for this indication starts at 2.5 mg injected subcutaneously once weekly, with the dose increased to 5 mg after 4 weeks, and further increased in 2.5 mg increments after a minimum of 4 weeks on the current dose as needed for glycemic control, up to a maximum of 15 mg once weekly.[17][18] Subsequently, the FDA approved tirzepatide under the proprietary name Zepbound on November 8, 2023, for chronic weight management as an adjunct to a reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity in adults with an initial body mass index (BMI) of 30 kg/m² or greater (obesity) or 27 kg/m² or greater (overweight) in the presence of at least one weight-related comorbid condition such as hypertension, dyslipidemia, type 2 diabetes mellitus, obstructive sleep apnea, or cardiovascular disease.[19][20] The FDA-approved dosing for weight management follows the same titration schedule, starting at 2.5 mg once weekly and escalating to maintenance doses of 5 mg, 10 mg, or 15 mg once weekly, with the 2.5 mg dose intended only for treatment initiation and not for chronic management.[20][21] The European Medicines Agency (EMA) granted a marketing authorization for tirzepatide (Mounjaro) on September 15, 2022, for the treatment of adults with insufficiently controlled type 2 diabetes as an adjunct to diet and exercise, either as monotherapy when metformin is inappropriate or in addition to other antidiabetic medicinal products.[22][23] The EMA's approved indication was later expanded to include weight management as an adjunct to a reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity for weight management, including weight loss and weight maintenance, in adults with an initial BMI of ≥30 kg/m² (obesity) or ≥27 kg/m² to <30 kg/m² (overweight) with at least one weight-related comorbidity.[24][22] The FDA prescribing information for Mounjaro carries a boxed warning for the risk of thyroid C-cell tumors, noting that tirzepatide caused dose-dependent and treatment-duration-dependent thyroid C-cell tumors in rats, and it is contraindicated in patients with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) or in patients with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2 (MEN 2).[18] This warning is also reflected in the EMA's product information, which advises that tirzepatide is contraindicated in patients with a personal or family history of MTC or in patients with MEN 2.[22] Both agencies list warnings and precautions for acute pancreatitis, hypoglycemia with concomitant use of insulin secretagogues or insulin, hypersensitivity reactions, acute kidney injury, severe gastrointestinal adverse reactions, diabetic retinopathy complications in patients with a history thereof, acute gallbladder disease, and pulmonary aspiration during anesthesia or deep sedation.[18][22] The FDA label specifically states that Mounjaro is not recommended in patients with severe gastroparesis.[18] The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) in England recommends tirzepatide for treating type 2 diabetes alongside diet and exercise in adults only under specific criteria: when triple therapy with metformin and two other oral antidiabetic drugs is ineffective, not tolerated, or contraindicated, and the patient has a BMI of 35 kg/m² or more with specific psychological or other medical problems associated with obesity, or a BMI of less than 35 kg/m² where insulin therapy would have significant occupational implications or weight loss would benefit other significant obesity-related complications.[25][26] NICE guidance specifies using lower BMI thresholds, usually reduced by 2.5 kg/m², for people from South Asian, Chinese, other Asian, Middle Eastern, Black African, or African-Caribbean family backgrounds.[25][26] The NICE guidance for weight management advises a starting dose of 2.5 mg once weekly, with titration by 2.5 mg every 4 weeks to recommended maintenance doses of 5 mg, 10 mg, or 15 mg once weekly, and recommends assessing treatment response after 6 months on the highest tolerated dose.[27] The EMA's assessment similarly relied on the SURPASS trial program for the diabetes indication and the SURMOUNT trials for weight management.[24][28][23] The pharmacokinetic profile supporting the once-weekly dosing is consistent across agencies, with a mean half-life of approximately 5 days, an absolute bioavailability of about 80%, and steady-state concentrations achieved after 4 weeks of administration.[21][29][22]
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_11\_codex_stdout.txt:201:   72: [13] The real-world safety profile of tirzepatide - PMC - NIH — https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11473560/ (tier T4)
