.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1383:outputs\audits\v25\_codex_stdout.txt:3574:+| 1. Citations | **BEAT_ONE** | V25 bibliography has 40 entries, including NEJM SURPASS-2 at report lines 67 and 77, plus FDA/EMA/NICE/HC regulatory sources at lines 91-105. Manifest confirms a 414-source corpus and 391 selected evidence rows at `manifest.json` lines 17-30 and 46-74. This beats ChatGPT's smaller cited-source footprint and still covers FDA/EMA/NICE/HC breadth. It does **not** beat Gemini on breadth: Gemini has 42 works cited and explicit Health Canada sources at competitor lines 835-857. V25 also lacks first-class SURPASS-1 Rosenstock/Lancet, SURPASS-3 Ludvik/Lancet, and SURMOUNT-1 Jastreboff primary citations in the final bibliography; instead it cites SURPASS-2 NEJM directly and leans on meta/review or secondary sources for other trial evidence. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1384:outputs\audits\v25\_codex_stdout.txt:3575:+| 2. Regulatory | **BEAT_ONE** | V25 restored a dedicated Regulatory section at report lines 23-25 and covers FDA Mounjaro/Zepbound approvals, EMA authorization/weight-management indication, boxed warnings, contraindications, dosing, device presentations, PK, and NICE criteria. That is broader than ChatGPT's US/EU-focused prescribing section, which notes FDA/EMA dose escalation and warning differences at competitor lines 966-982. V25 loses to Gemini's regulatory-risk synthesis: Gemini devotes separate sections to Health Canada/FDA hypoglycemia, thyroid C-cell warnings, perioperative aspiration, KwikPen, and counterfeits at lines 530-552 and 573-639. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1385:outputs\audits\v25\_codex_stdout.txt:3576:+| 3. Jurisdictional | **BEAT_ONE** | V25 includes US, EMA/EU, UK/NICE, and Canada: the Canadian Product Monograph is cited at report line 99, and the Regulatory prose notes its Serious Warnings and Precautions box at line 25. That beats ChatGPT, which explicitly compares US and EMA language but does not show Canada/NICE specificity in the cited passages at lines 966-982. It loses to Gemini, which has much more jurisdictional detail: Health Canada is named in the intro at lines 29-32, in thyroid warnings at 530-541, in perioperative aspiration at 573-603, and in counterfeit-product coverage at 629-639. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1388:outputs\audits\v25\_codex_stdout.txt:3585:+2. **Primary-trial citation coverage is uneven.** SURPASS-2 NEJM is present as a first-class source, but SURPASS-1 Rosenstock/Lancet, SURPASS-3 Ludvik/Lancet, and SURMOUNT-1 Jastreboff are not first-class final bibliography entries.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1390:outputs\audits\v25\_codex_stdout.txt:3599:+| M-41a | **Successful for Regulatory restoration.** It restored the six-section outline and Regulatory section, with FDA/EMA/HC/NICE content at report line 25 and sources at bibliography lines 91-105. |
