.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1461:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:71:Regulatory source retrieval itself is effective: all 12 T3 bibliography entries resolve or are live-index verified, including FDA accessdata PDFs, EMA PDFs, and NICE PDFs/pages. The report also uses regulatory evidence for content V17 could not support: FDA Mounjaro T2D indication, FDA Zepbound weight-management indication, EMA Mounjaro T2D/weight indications, and NICE T2D recommendation criteria.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1463:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:75:NICE is handled cleanly. TA924 recommends tirzepatide for T2D only under defined criteria after ineffective/not tolerated/contraindicated triple oral therapy, BMI thresholds/occupational implications/obesity-related complications, and lower BMI thresholds for specified ethnic backgrounds. TA1026 obesity prescribing guidance is correctly kept separate from T2D recommendation logic.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1465:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:81:V18 improves materially over V17 on the regulatory-framing gap. V17 had no regulatory-agency URLs and relied on trial/pharmacovigilance sources for safety. V18 has a dedicated Regulatory section, 12 T3 cites, FDA/EMA/NICE source diversity, and practical dosing/contraindication/recommendation content. Integration is reasonably clean as a final section rather than a pasted appendix: it follows efficacy, safety, comparative, and dose-response sections and links dosing/indications/warnings to earlier safety material.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1466:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:83:The T2D focus is mostly maintained. FDA Mounjaro, EMA Mounjaro, and NICE TA924 directly answer adult T2D; Zepbound/NICE TA1026 obesity material is relevant to the weight-loss side of the user question but should stay explicitly separate from glycemic-control labeling.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1467:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:85:Jurisdiction differences are only partially surfaced. FDA vs EMA indications are separated, and NICE is named as UK guidance. But the safety warning/contraindication sentence conflates FDA and EMA. This is the decisive regression versus V17: V17 lacked regulatory framing, but it also lacked this regulatory overclaim.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1468:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:88:Compared with `state/compare_chatgpt_dr.txt`, V18 is closer to tier-1 DR on jurisdiction-aware framing because it now cites FDA, EMA, and NICE and includes label/guidance-level practical prescribing content. It still falls short of ChatGPT DR's regulatory precision, which explicitly states that U.S. labeling and EMA SmPC are not interchangeable.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1470:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\findings.md:93:CONTINUE. Next fix: add a regulatory-jurisdiction verifier that flags any sentence combining FDA/EMA/NICE/Health Canada claims unless each jurisdiction-specific clause is supported by a source from that jurisdiction, and require label contraindications to be stated per jurisdiction. For this report, rewrite the FDA/EMA safety sentence to separate FDA boxed warning/MTC-MEN2 contraindications from EMA SmPC hypersensitivity contraindication and warnings/precautions, then resweep the output.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1473:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\codex_stderr.log:30:  `regulatory_anchors` (FDA accessdata, EMA, Health Canada, NICE,
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1477:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\codex_stderr.log:47:  NICE guidance
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1482:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\codex_stderr.log:64:     NICE recommendation sentences are present and cite the right
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1485:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\codex_stderr.log:77:   - Are jurisdiction differences (FDA vs EMA vs NICE) surfaced
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1493:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\codex_stderr.log:156:Tirzepatide is approved by the FDA under the proprietary name Mounjaro as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus.[24] The FDA-approved dosing regimen starts at 2.5 mg subcutaneously once weekly, with increases in 2.5 mg increments after a minimum of 4 weeks on the current dose, up to a maximum of 15 mg once weekly.[24][25] The European Medicines Agency (EMA) authorizes tirzepatide (Mounjaro) for the same T2DM indication in adults, as monotherapy when metformin is inappropriate or as an add-on to other antidiabetic medicines.[26][27] The EMA also approves tirzepatide for weight management as an adjunct to a reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity in adults with an initial BMI of ≥30 kg/m² (obesity) or ≥27 kg/m² to <30 kg/m² (overweight) in the presence of at least one weight-related comorbidity.[28][26] For the chronic weight management indication, the FDA approved tirzepatide under the name Zepbound, with an identical starting and titration schedule up to 15 mg once weekly.[29][30] A key safety warning from both agencies is a boxed warning for risk of thyroid C-cell tumors, as tirzepatide caused thyroid C-cell tumors in rats, though human relevance is unknown.[31][32] Consequently, tirzepatide is contraindicated in patients with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) or in patients with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2 (MEN 2).[31][32] Other warnings and precautions common to the labels include the risk of severe gastrointestinal adverse reactions, acute pancreatitis, hypoglycemia with concomitant insulin secretagogues or insulin, hypersensitivity reactions, acute kidney injury, acute gallbladder disease, and potential impact on absorption of oral medications due to delayed gastric emptying.[31][32] The EMA product information additionally notes a mean increase in heart rate and includes diabetic retinopathy complications and pulmonary aspiration during anesthesia as precautions.[26] The UK's National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) recommends tirzepatide for treating T2DM in adults only under specific conditions: when triple therapy with metformin and two other oral antidiabetic drugs is ineffective, not tolerated, or contraindicated, and the patient has a BMI of 35 kg/m² or more with associated psychological or medical problems, or a BMI under 35 kg/m² where insulin therapy has significant occupational implications or weight loss would benefit other obesity-related complications.[33][34] NICE guidance also specifies using lower BMI thresholds for people from certain ethnic backgrounds.[33] For weight management, NICE provides a prescribing guide, confirming the starting dose of 2.5 mg once weekly and titration by 2.5 mg every 4 weeks to recommended maintenance doses of 5 mg, 10 mg, or 15 mg once weekly.[35]
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1505:outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_9\codex_stderr.log:227:[33] [PDF] Tirzepatide for treating type 2 diabetes - NICE — https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta924/documents/674-2 (tier T3)
