.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1989:outputs\codex_findings\autoloop_v2_protocol_review\_codex_stdout.txt:280:   reason: V23 has 31 bibliography entries with reasonable domain diversity, including Springer/PMC/Nature/FDA/EMA/NICE/Frontiers/Cureus, but the report itself admits only 16% T1 primary studies and the bibliography foregrounds post-hoc, indirect-comparison, NMA, and regulatory sources rather than the core SURPASS-1 through SURPASS-6 primary trial publications (report.md lines 25 and 59-90; bibliography.json lines 1-219). ChatGPT explicitly prioritizes core SURPASS publications and lists direct SURPASS primary URLs, albeit messily duplicated, while Gemini has 42 works cited and covers SURPASS-1 through SURPASS-6 plus Health Canada/FDA items, so V23 does not beat either on count plus primary-trial coverage (state/compare_chatgpt_dr.txt lines 50-66 and 1129-1221; state/compare_gemini_dr.txt lines 680-858).
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1991:outputs\codex_findings\autoloop_v2_protocol_review\_codex_stdout.txt:282:   reason: V23 gives unusually dense FDA, EMA, and NICE specificity in one regulatory paragraph, including approval dates, indications, dose titration, boxed warning/contraindications, NICE diabetes criteria, lower BMI thresholds, weight-management review timing, and pharmacokinetics (report.md lines 15-17). It beats ChatGPT's narrower U.S./EMA practical-prescribing discussion, but it does not beat Gemini because Gemini adds Health Canada-specific product-monograph, aspiration, KwikPen, and counterfeit-product warnings that V23 lacks (state/compare_chatgpt_dr.txt lines 966-982; state/compare_gemini_dr.txt lines 608-652 and 828-847).
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1992:outputs\codex_findings\autoloop_v2_protocol_review\_codex_stdout.txt:284:   reason: V23 attributes claims to named authorities rather than generic regulators, distinguishing FDA Mounjaro/Zepbound, EMA marketing authorization/variation, and NICE TA criteria with jurisdiction-specific BMI and dosing language (report.md lines 17 and 76-88). It is more jurisdictionally precise than ChatGPT's FDA/EMA-only contrast, but it does not beat Gemini because Gemini separately attributes Canadian approvals and safety actions to Health Canada/Drug and Health Products Portal sources (state/compare_chatgpt_dr.txt lines 974-982; state/compare_gemini_dr.txt lines 626-652 and 835-847).
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\_codex_stdout.txt:1995:outputs\codex_findings\autoloop_v2_protocol_review\_codex_stdout.txt:299:2. Add Health Canada specificity alongside FDA, EMA, and NICE, including the Canadian product monograph / Summary Basis of Decision and any jurisdiction-specific safety communications.
