.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\findings.md:7:   reason: V21 retrieves the broadest and most regulator-specific set: FDA Mounjaro NDA summary and clinical pharmacology reviews, FDA Mounjaro label, FDA Zepbound NDA/label/press material, EMA EPAR/product information/variation assessment reports, NICE TA924 documents and rollout article, and a Canadian Product Monograph (report.md:21,82-96). ChatGPT cites FDA statistical review, U.S. prescribing information, and EMA product information but not NICE or Health Canada (compare_chatgpt_dr.txt:51-52,966-981,1135-1166). Gemini cites FDA labels and multiple Health Canada/Canadian safety sources, but not EMA or NICE (compare_gemini_dr.txt:828-857).
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\findings.md:9:   reason: V21 usually attributes regulatory claims to the specific authority: FDA approval/dosing/boxed warning, EMA EU marketing authorization and indication, NICE criteria, and Canadian Product Monograph contraindication/warnings (report.md:21). It has one broad sentence that "key labeling warnings and precautions are consistent across authorities" (report.md:21), which is less precise than ChatGPT's explicit warning that U.S. and EU texts are not interchangeable (compare_chatgpt_dr.txt:35-49,974-981). Gemini is weaker: it says updates were issued by "both" FDA and Health Canada (compare_gemini_dr.txt:30-32), says "Both FDA and Health Canada guidelines mandate" dose-reduction consideration without separating label language (compare_gemini_dr.txt:530-532), and extrapolates a Health Canada perioperative review into global protocol shifts and withholding practices (compare_gemini_dr.txt:596-603). V21 therefore beats Gemini but not ChatGPT.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\findings.md:24:2. Add structural depth: a trial-comparison table, dose-response table, direct-vs-indirect comparator table, regulatory subsection broken out by FDA/EMA/NICE/Health Canada, and an evidence-gaps/limitations section.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\findings.md:30:V21's regulatory retrieval is genuinely strong and broader than both competitors, especially because it includes NICE and EMA documents as well as FDA and Canadian material. That advantage is not enough to terminate the loop because V21 loses to both competitors on trial framing, structure, and narrative depth. The advisory manifest flags should not drive the verdict; the content-level issue is that V21 reads like a compact evidence synthesis, while the competitors read like full deep-research reports.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:55:2. **Regulatory retrieval**: FDA/EMA/NICE/Health Canada/EU sources
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:133:"C:\\Program Files\\PowerShell\\7\\pwsh.exe" -Command 'rg -n "''^(#|##|###)|''^'"\\[|References|Bibliography|FDA|EMA|NICE|Health Canada|SURPASS|boxed|warning|noninferior|superior|superiority|noninferiority\" outputs/full_scale_v21/clinical/clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm/report.md state/compare_chatgpt_dr.txt state/compare_gemini_dr.txt" in C:\POLARIS
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:202:state/compare_gemini_dr.txt:687:3.​ Lilly's SURPASS-1 results published in The Lancet show tirzepatide's superior A1C 
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:235:outputs/full_scale_v21/clinical/clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm/report.md:21:Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved tirzepatide under the trade name Mounjaro in 2022 as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus.[24][25] The FDA-approved dosing regimen starts at 2.5 mg once weekly, with increases in 2.5 mg increments after a minimum of 4 weeks on the current dose, up to a maximum of 15 mg once weekly.[24][25] The FDA label carries a boxed warning for risk of thyroid C-cell tumors, based on findings in rats, and contraindicates tirzepatide in patients with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma or Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2.[26] The FDA later approved tirzepatide for chronic weight management under the trade name Zepbound in 2023, indicated as an adjunct to a reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity for adults with obesity (BMI ≥30 kg/m²) or overweight (BMI ≥27 kg/m²) with at least one weight-related comorbid condition.[27][28] The European Medicines Agency (EMA) granted a marketing authorization for Mounjaro valid throughout the EU on 15 September 2022.[29] The EMA's approved indication for type 2 diabetes is for the treatment of adults, adolescents, and children aged 10 years and above with insufficiently controlled disease as an adjunct to diet and exercise, as monotherapy when metformin is inappropriate or in addition to other antidiabetic products.[30] The EMA also approved an indication for weight management, defined as an adjunct to a reduced-calorie diet and increased physical activity for weight management in adults with an initial BMI of ≥30 kg/m² (obesity) or ≥27 kg/m² to <30 kg/m² (overweight) in the presence of at least one weight-related comorbidity.[31][30][32] The UK's National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) recommends tirzepatide for treating type 2 diabetes in adults only under specific criteria: when triple therapy with metformin and two other oral drugs is ineffective, not tolerated, or contraindicated, and the patient has a BMI of 35 kg/m² or more with specific problems associated with obesity, or a BMI below 35 kg/m² where insulin therapy has significant occupational implications or weight loss would benefit other significant obesity-related complications.[33][34] NICE's recommendation is contingent upon a commercial arrangement that makes tirzepatide available to the NHS at a cost-effective price.[33][34] For weight management, NICE recommends tirzepatide as an option for people with a BMI of more than 35 and at least one weight-related illness, with an initial rollout prioritized for those in specialist services.[35] Key labeling warnings and precautions are consistent across authorities and include risks of severe gastrointestinal adverse reactions, acute pancreatitis, acute kidney injury, acute gallbladder disease, hypersensitivity reactions, and hypoglycemia with concomitant insulin or insulin secretagogues.[36][26][30] The FDA and EMA labels also warn that tirzepatide delays gastric emptying, which can impact the absorption of concomitantly administered oral medications, necessitating guidance for patients using oral contraceptives.[25][37][30] The Canadian Product Monograph for Zepbound similarly contraindicates use in patients with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma and warns of gastrointestinal adverse reactions and the potential for drug interactions due to delayed gastric emptying.[38]
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:253:outputs/full_scale_v21/clinical/clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm/report.md:72:[14] The real-world safety profile of tirzepatide - PMC - NIH — https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11473560/ (tier T4)
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:272:outputs/full_scale_v21/clinical/clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm/report.md:91:[33] [PDF] Tirzepatide for treating type 2 diabetes - NICE — https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta924/documents/674-2 (tier T3)
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:273:outputs/full_scale_v21/clinical/clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm/report.md:92:[34] [PDF] Tirzepatide for treating type 2 diabetes | NICE — https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta924/resources/tirzepatide-for-treating-type-2-diabetes-pdf-82615547603653 (tier T3)
