.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:6:specific_domains_to_add: ["pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov", "mdpi.com", "acc.org", "pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov"]
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:10:  Cycle 8 is materially better than cycle 7 because it produced one releasable thin-corpus report instead of zero releases. The released tirzepatide report has resolving citations and no obvious unsupported numeric claim, but its tier accounting is not clean: bibliography [1] is an R10 false T1, and the live corpus still has a false-T1 MDPI systematic review/meta-analysis. All remaining T1 hallucinations are narrow R10 fallback cases on biomedical aggregator/journal domains or a professional-society PDF, so a targeted M-15 is preferable to restoring the blanket T1 primary-signal requirement that caused the cycle-7 zero-release failure. The seven aborts are honest under the current adequacy contract; correcting the false T1 rows would make the aborted corpora weaker, not releasable.
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:52:| `clinical_tirzepatide_t2dm` | `https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10115620/` | T1 | T4 | Demote PMC articles when title/content/pub-type signals perspective, review, guidance, or clinical overview. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:54:| `clinical_afib_anticoagulation` | `https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12240022/` | T1 | T4 | Add `guideline`, `guidelines`, `guidance`, `practical guidance`, and consensus/practice-guide signals as R10 blockers. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:55:| `clinical_afib_anticoagulation` | ACC DOAC dosing PDF | T1 | T3/T4 | Demote professional-society PDFs with path/title signals such as `tools`, `practice-support`, `information-graphics`, `dosing`, or `guideline`; never R10-promote `acc.org` PDFs. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:64:3. Treat `pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov` and `pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov` as aggregators requiring article-type/title/content signals before T1.
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_15\findings.md:65:4. Treat professional-society PDFs on `acc.org` as T3/T4 unless explicit primary-study metadata is present.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:17:  Sentence-level audit: the first two efficacy sentences are numerically supported by the Lilly/PRNewswire page, but this is not acceptable lead evidence for SURPASS-3/5 when Lancet/JAMA primary trial papers exist. The SURPASS-2 head-to-head sentence cites an ADA late-breaking abstract, not the NEJM trial. The safety section cites a systematic review that explicitly flags high-dose hypoglycemia and discontinuation, but the report omits those material caveats. The boxed-warning sentence cites a Facebook post rather than an FDA label or prescribing information. The final type 1 diabetes sentence is outside the scoped adult T2D question. The limitations section honestly reports low-tier skew, but that admission does not cure the report.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:52:| SURPASS-5 15 mg reduced HbA1c 2.59% and weight 10.9 kg. | [1] PRNewswire/Lilly release. | Numerically supported; should cite JAMA/SURPASS-5 primary paper. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:53:| Meta-analysis found HbA1c -1.94% and weight -8.47 kg vs control. | [2] MDPI Pharmaceutics SR/MA. | Supported; acceptable secondary evidence, not sufficient alone. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:78:| pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10115620 | T1 | T4 review | Disagree; overclassified. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:87:| pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11473560 | T1 | T1 observational pharmacovigilance | Agree, but causal limits needed. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:89:| pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12127604 | T4 | Case report | Agree. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_1\findings.md:109:2. Re-run classifier or manually pin tiers for NEJM/Lancet/JAMA primary RCTs and PMC review articles; do not allow review pages to masquerade as T1 primary evidence.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\findings.md:3:Overall verdict: **PARTIAL, not BEAT_BOTH overall, not releaseable**. V27 is better than V26 on NICE restoration and Health Canada retention, but it still does not beat both ChatGPT DR and Gemini 3.1 Pro DR across all seven dimensions. The manifest itself blocks release: `status=partial_qwen_advisory`, `release_allowed=false`, with qwen `citation_tightness` and `multi_axis` revision reasons; evidence selection also short-circuited at `pool_size<=max_rows (385/600)`, so M-42c/d/e selector floors were correct but inactive.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\findings.md:7:| 1. Citations | **BEAT_ONE** | V27 has **47 bibliography entries** at report lines 63-110, beating ChatGPT's smaller cited-source footprint (ChatGPT bibliography URLs begin at compare lines 1129-1221 and include duplicates). It restores first-class SURPASS-1 and SURPASS-4 primaries: SURPASS-1 Lancet is [9] at report line 72 (`https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(21)01324-6`), SURPASS-4 Lancet is [18] at line 81 (`https://doi.org/10.1016/s0140-6736(21)02188-7`), and SURPASS-5 JAMA/PubMed is [2] at line 65 (`https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35133415/`). But V27 still loses to Gemini on primary-trial narrative coverage: Gemini has dedicated SURPASS-1 through -6 and SURMOUNT-2 sections at compare lines 86-207 and 322-351, while V27 relies heavily on meta-analyses/post-hocs for core comparative and dose-response claims at report lines 5, 13, and 21. V27 also lacks visible first-class SURMOUNT-1/Jastreboff primary citation; obesity-without-T2D evidence appears as a Bayesian NMA [4] at line 67. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\findings.md:8:| 2. Regulatory | **BEAT_BOTH** | V27 Regulatory is dense and primary-regulator anchored: FDA Mounjaro/Zepbound approvals, dose escalation, boxed warning, contraindications, retinopathy/aspiration/KwikPen warnings at report line 25 with FDA sources [35]-[39] lines 98-102 (`accessdata.fda.gov`, `fda.gov`); EMA authorization, pediatric/T2D language, weight-management indication, additional monitoring, SmPC warnings with [40]-[42] lines 103-105 (`ema.europa.eu`); Health Canada product monographs [43]-[44] lines 106-107 (`https://pdf.hres.ca/dpd_pm/00073189.PDF`, `00083504.PDF`); NICE T2D and obesity guidance [45]-[47] lines 108-110 (`nice.org.uk`). ChatGPT is mostly FDA/EMA prescribing at compare lines 968-982. Gemini is deep on FDA/Health Canada safety updates and counterfeit risk at compare lines 530-639, but lacks NICE. V27's four-jurisdiction regulator span beats both on breadth and is close enough on depth because it includes KwikPen, aspiration, HC monographs, and NICE stopping/titration rules. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\findings.md:9:| 3. Jurisdictional | **BEAT_BOTH** | V27 names and differentiates US FDA, EMA, Health Canada, and NICE in one regulatory paragraph, not just boilerplate. NICE criteria include BMI thresholds, occupational insulin implications, ethnic-threshold adjustment, tirzepatide titration, and 6-month 5% stopping rule at report line 25 with NICE URLs [45]-[47]. Health Canada content is label-specific: Canadian indication and serious-warnings box at report line 25 with product monograph URLs [43]-[44]. ChatGPT has US/EMA label comparison only at compare lines 968-982. Gemini has strong Health Canada specificity at lines 530-539 and 584-639, but no NICE. V27 therefore beats ChatGPT on non-US spread and beats Gemini on jurisdictional spread, despite Gemini's Canada depth. |
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\findings.md:17:M-43 partially worked: V27 restores NICE from V26's zero to three bibliography entries and brings NICE back into final prose. It does **not** restore the V25 NICE baseline of four, and preservation still fails NICE by one.
.\outputs\codex_findings\dr_output_pass_14_v27\findings.md:28:2. FDA and NICE preservation regressed versus V25: FDA 5 vs 7, NICE 3 vs 4.
