rview ACS & Open Access Partners Blog Events Publications CONTENT TYPES All Types SUBJECTS Publications: All Types Download Hi-Res Image Download to MS-PowerPoint Cite This: ACS Biomater. Sci. Eng. 2021 , 7 , 9 , 4048-4076 ADVERTISEMENT RETURN TO ISSUE PREV Review NEXT Engineering Hydrogel Adhesion for Biomedical Applications via Chemical Design of the Junction Giovanni Bovone Giovanni Bovone Macromolecular Engineering Laboratory, Department of Mechanical and Process Engineering, ETH Zurich, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland More by Giovanni Bovone http://orcid.org/0000-0002-8508-0737 , Oksana Y. Dudaryeva Oksana Y. Dudaryeva Macromolecular Engineering Laboratory, Department of Mechanical and Process Engineering, ETH Zurich, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland More by Oksana Y. Dudaryeva , Bruno Marco-Dufort Bruno Marco-Dufort Macromolecular Engineering Laboratory, Department of Mechanical and Process Engineering, ETH Zurich, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland More by Bruno Marco-Dufort http://orcid.org/0000-0001-9098-9964 , and Mark W. Tibbitt * Mark W. Tibbitt Macromolecular Engineering Laboratory, Department of Mechanical and Process Engineering, ETH Zurich, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland * Email: [email&#160;protected] . Phone: +41 44 632 25 16. More by Mark W. Tibbitt http://orcid.org/0000-0002-4917-7187 Cite this: ACS Biomater. Sci. Eng. 2021 , 7 , 9 , 4048–4076 Publication Date (Web) : April 1, 2021 Publication History Received 1 December 2020 Accepted 10 March 2021 Published online 1 April 2021 Published in issue 13 September 2021 https://doi.org/10.1021/acsbiomaterials.0c01677 Copyright © 2021 The Authors. Published by American Chemical Society . This publication is licensed under CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 . License Summary* You are free to share (copy and redistribute) this article in any medium or format within the parameters below: Creative Commons (CC): This is a Creative Commons license. Attribution (BY): Credit must be given to the creator. Non-Commercial (NC): Only non-commercial uses of the work are permitted. No Derivatives (ND): Derivative works may be created for non-commercial purposes, but sharing is prohibited. View full license *Disclaimer This summary highlights only some of the key features and terms of the actual license. It is not a license and has no legal value. Carefully review the actual license before using these materials. This publication is Open Access under the license indicated. Learn More Article Views 21485 Altmetric - Citations 41 LEARN ABOUT THESE METRICS Article Views are the COUNTER-compliant sum of full text article downloads since November 2008 (both PDF and HTML) across all institutions and individuals. These metrics are regularly updated to reflect usage leading up to the last few days. Citations are the number of other articles citing this article, calculated by Crossref and updated daily. Find more information about Crossref citation counts. The Altmetric Attention Score is a quantitative measure of the attention that a research article has received online. Clicking on the donut icon will load a page at altmetric.com with additional details about the score and the social media presence for the given article. Find more information on the Altmetric Attention Score and how the score is calculated. Share Add to View In Add Full Text with Reference Add Description Export RIS Citation Citation and abstract Citation and references More Options Share on Facebook Twitter Wechat Linked In Reddit PDF (7 MB) Get e-Alerts close SUBJECTS: Functional groups , Hydrogels , Materials , Mathematical methods , Surface interactions Get e-Alerts Abstract High Resolution Image Download MS PowerPoint Slide Hydrogel adhesion inherently relies on engineering the contact surface at soft and hydrated interfaces. Upon contact, adhesion normally occurs through the formation of chemical or physical interactions between the disparate surfaces. The ability to form these adhesion junctions is challenging for hydrogels as the interfaces are wet and deformable and often contain low densities of functional groups. In this Review, we link the design of the binding chemistries or adhesion junctions, whether covalent, dynamic covalent, supramolecular, or physical, to the emergent adhesive properties of soft and hydrated interfaces. Wet adhesion is useful for bonding to or between tissues and implants for a range of biomedical applications. We highlight several recent and emerging adhesive hydrogels for use in biomedicine in the context of efficient junction design. The main focus is on engineering hydrogel adhesion through molecular design of the junctions to tailor the adhesion strength, reversibility, stability, and response to environmental stimuli. This publication is licensed under CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 . License Summary* You are free to share (copy and redistribute) this article in any medium or format within the parameters below: Creative Commons (CC): This is a Creative Commons license. Attribution (BY): Credit must be given to the creator. Non-Commercial (NC): Only non-commercial uses of the work are permitted. No Derivatives (ND): Derivative works may be created for non-commercial purposes, but sharing is prohibited. View full license *Disclaimer This summary highlights only some of the key features and terms of the actual license. It is not a license and has no legal value. Carefully review the actual license before using these materials. License Summary* You are free to share (copy and redistribute) this article in any medium or format within the parameters below: Creative Commons (CC): This is a Creative Commons license. Attribution (BY): Credit must be given to the creator. Non-Commercial (NC): Only non-commercial uses of the work are permitted. No Derivatives (ND): Derivative works may be created for non-commercial purposes, but sharing is prohibited. View full license *Disclaimer This summary highlights only some of the key features and terms of the actual license. It is not a license and has no legal value. Carefully review the actual license before using these materials. License Summary* You are free to share (copy and redistribute) this article in any medium or format within the parameters below: Creative Commons (CC): This is a Creative Commons license. Attribution (BY): Credit must be given to the creator. Non-Commercial (NC): Only non-commercial uses of the work are permitted. No Derivatives (ND): Derivative works may be created for non-commercial purposes, but sharing is prohibited. View full license *Disclaimer This summary highlights only some of the key features and terms of the actual license. It is not a license and has no legal value. Carefully review the actual license before using these materials. License Summary* You are free to share (copy and redistribute) this article in any medium or format within the parameters below: Creative Commons (CC): This is a Creative Commons license. Attribution (BY): Credit must be given to the creator. Non-Commercial (NC): Only non-commercial uses of the work are permitted. No Derivatives (ND): Derivative works may be created for non-commercial purposes, but sharing is prohibited. View full license *Disclaimer This summary highlights only some of the key features and terms of the actual license. It is not a license and has no legal value. Carefully review the actual license before using these materials. License Summary* You are free to share (copy and redistribute) this article in any medium or format within the parameters below: Creative Commons (CC): This is a Creative Commons license. Attribution (BY): Credit must be given to the creator. Non-Commercial (NC): Only non-commercial uses of the work are permitted. No Derivatives (ND): Derivative works may be created for non-commercial purposes, but sharing is prohibited. View full license *Disclaimer This summary highlights only some of the key features and terms of the actual license. It is not a license and has no legal value. Carefully review the actual license before using these materials. KEYWORDS: hydrogel adhesion biomedical adhesives surface chemistry junction design SPECIAL ISSUE This article is part of the Advanced Biomedical Hydrogels special issue. 1. Introduction ARTICLE SECTIONS Jump To Hydrogel adhesion describes the formation of connections or junctions between two surfaces in which at least one of the surfaces is a hydrogel and the other surface can be any type of material, hard or soft. Hydrogel adhesion is useful in engineering and medicine and is implemented in a wide range of applications including tissue adhesives and sealants, (1−4) drug delivery, (5,6) additive manufacturing, (7) soft robotics, (8,9) and sensing and electronics. (10) In biomedicine, there is specific interest in adhering hydrogels to tissues for the closure of wounds, (2) sealing of damaged sections of organs, (11) and the development of stretchable electronics. (12) In addition, hydrogel adhesion to hard and dry surfaces is useful for engineering adaptive and responsive devices. (13−16) Hydrogels are water-swollen polymer networks that, by definition, include a significant volume fraction of water and have a low polymer content. Therefore, effective adhesion of hydrogels on a variety of surfaces presents unique challenges. Due to the low density of polymer chains, many hydrogels are inherently soft (Young’s modulus ∼0.01–10 kPa) and deformable. Further, the majority of the volume of a typical hydrogel is composed of polar water molecules that do not participate actively in joining the two materials and, in some cases, can inhibit adhesion. (17) To overcome these challenges, strong and functional hydrogel adhesion has been achieved by combining different hydrogel backbones, (11) preparation techniques, (2,18) and adhesion topologies and bond chemistries. (19) In general, the process of adhesion of two or more distinct materials relies on the formation of adhesion junctions or connections ( Figure 1 ). Throughout this Review, we use adhesion junction to refer to the interactions that link materials at an adhesive interface, adherend to refer to the materials that are being connected, and adhesive to refer to the component that forms the adhesion junctions. The adhesive properties, such as the strength of adhesion, reversibility, stability, and response to environmental stimuli, are given by the design of the adhesion interface. Many aspects of this topic are discussed in two excellent and comprehensive reviews. Suo and co-workers focused on the synergy of adhesion topology, chemistry, and mechanics. (20) Recently, Nam and Mooney discussed the fundamental mechanisms of tissue adhesion and developed rational guidelines to design adhesives for specific tissues. (21) Other reviews discussing th\n\n--- PAGE: Polymers, Volume 16, Issue 5 (March-1 2024) – 159 articles - MDPI ---\nURL: https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4360/16/5\nCONTENT:\n(https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4360/16/5#main) You are currently on the new version of our website. Access the old version here. Close [![MDPI](https://mdpi-res.com/cdn-cgi/image/w=56,h=30/https://mdpi-res.com/data/mdpi-logo-black.svg)![MDPI](https://mdpi-res.com/cdn-cgi/image/w=70,h=56/https://mdpi-res.com/data/mdpi-logo-black.svg)](https://www.mdpi.com/) * Journals * [All Journals](https://www.mdpi.com/about/journals) * [Journal Finder](https://www.mdpi.com/about/journalfinder) * [Proceedings Series](https://www.mdpi.com/about/proceedings) * [Propose a Journal](https://www.mdpi.com/about/journals/proposal) * Topics By Subjects * [Biology & Life Sciences](https://www.mdpi.com/topics?facets=NobwRAlgJmBcYGcCuAjAVgUwMYBcFgBowA3AQwBskM4wBGQsc0lDcmgIQgHtyuBzAJ4ACAGRCAMhABmGIQGUsEDADssGfAF8AukA) * [Business & Economics](https://www.mdpi.com/topics?facets=NobwRAlgJmBcYGcCuAjAVgUwMYBcFgBowA3AQwBskM4wAmQsc0lDcmgISQQgDsMEEAAgBkggKJYA9j0kBbCFnwBfALpA) * [Chemistry & Materials](https://www.mdpi.com/topics?facets=NobwRAlgJmBcYGcCuAjAVgUwMYBcFgBowA3AQwBskM4wBmQsc0lDcmgYQAsMBbCBHACcAngAIAZKICypHBkEQKCUQGUsE