d Feedback](https://www.mdpi.com/support/feedback) [](https://www.mdpi.com/search)Search [](https://www.mdpi.com/search) Open mobile navigation 1. [Home](https://www.mdpi.com/) 2. [Journals](https://www.mdpi.com/about/journals) 3. [Nanomaterials](https://www.mdpi.com/journal/nanomaterials) 4. [Volume 11](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11) 5. [Issue 4](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4) 6. [10.3390/nano11040872](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872) [![](https://mdpi-res.com/cdn-cgi/image/w=32,h=32/https://mdpi-res.com/img/journals/nanomaterials-logo-sq.png?f1f561582aaa2e89)NanomaterialsNanomaterials](https://www.mdpi.com/journal/nanomaterials) Get Alerted Get Alerted Open CiteCite Open ShareShare [ Download PDF PDF ](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872/pdf) [Abstract](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Abstract)[Introduction](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Introduction)[Materials and Methods](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Materials_and_Methods)[Results and Discussion](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Results_and_Discussion)[Conclusions](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Conclusions)[Author Contributions](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Author_Contributions)[Funding](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Funding)[Data Availability Statement](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Data_Availability_Statement)[Conflicts of Interest](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Conflicts_of_Interest)[References](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#References)[Article Metrics](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872#Article_Metrics) * Article * ![Open Access](https://mdpi-res.com/cdn-cgi/image/w=14,h=14/https://mdpi-res.com/data/open-access.svg) 30 March 2021 # Prediction of Lap Shear Strength and Impact Peel Strength of Epoxy Adhesive by Machine Learning Approach Haisu Kang1, Ji Hee Lee1, Youngson Choe1,2,* and Seung Geol Lee1,3,* 1 School of Chemical Engineering, Pusan National University, Busan 46241, Korea 2 Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering, Pusan National University, Busan 46241, Korea 3 Department of Organic Material Science and Engineering, Pusan National University, Busan 46241, Korea * Authors to whom correspondence should be addressed. [Nanomaterials](https://www.mdpi.com/journal/nanomaterials)**2021** , _11_(4), 872; This article belongs to the Special Issue [Advances in Computational Materials Science on Functional Interfaces and Surfaces](https://www.mdpi.com/journal/nanomaterials/special_issues/nano_computational_surfaces) [Version Notes](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872/notes) [Order Reprints](https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872/reprints) ## Abstract In this study, an artificial neural network (ANN), which is a machine learning (ML) method, is used to predict the adhesion strength of structural epoxy adhesives. The data sets were obtained by testing the lap shear strength at room temperature and the impact peel strength at −40 °C for specimens of various epoxy adhesive formulations. The linear correlation analysis showed that the content of the catalyst, flexibilizer, and the curing agent in the epoxy formulation exhibited the highest correlation with the lap shear strength. Using the analyzed data sets, we constructed an ANN model and optimized it with the selection set and training set divided from the data sets. The obtained root mean square error (RMSE) and R2 values confirmed that each model was a suitable predictive model. The change of the lap shear strength and impact peel strength was predicted according to the change in the content of components shown to have a high linear correlation with the lap shear strength and the impact peel strength. Consequently, the contents of the formulation components that resulted in the optimum adhesive strength of epoxy were obtained by our prediction model. Keywords: [epoxy adhesive](https://www.mdpi.com/search?q=epoxy+adhesive); [machine learning](https://www.mdpi.com/search?q=machine+learning); [artificial neural network](https://www.mdpi.com/search?q=artificial+neural+network); [lap shear strength](https://www.mdpi.com/search?q=lap+shear+strength); [impact peel strength](https://www.mdpi.com/search?q=impact+peel+strength) ## 1. Introduction Structural adhesives are used in structural joints of transport devices such as automobiles or aircraft. Compared with bonding techniques such as conventional screws, mechanical coupling with bolts, or welding, structural adhesives deliver outstanding performance in increasing the structural stiffness, reducing vibrational noise, and reducing the weight of structures. In the early stage of their development, the use of structural adhesives was limited to the structural junctions of transport vehicles. However, structural adhesives are now broadly used for high-performance and customized structural designs, and the range of joints on which structural adhesives are used has been extended, which has greatly increased the demand for structural adhesives [1,2,3]. To be used for structural bonding, a structural adhesive is required to exhibit excellent adhesion strength in addition to superb resistance to impact and flexural deformation. An epoxy adhesive is a representative structural adhesive and is the most widely used adhesive with qualified performance. Epoxy adhesives largely consist of two parts: an epoxy resin and a curing agent. Epoxy resin is a thermosetting resin with various functional groups in its chemical structure, including epoxy (–O–) groups, which react with amino (–NH) groups in the curing agents. The reaction between epoxy groups in an epoxy resin and amino groups in a curing agent, i.e., the curing reaction, results in a crosslinking structure, which improves heat resistance, solvent resistance, and moisture resistance [2,3]. In practical applications, the epoxy resin is often modified for a specific purpose, or its additive composition is varied for desired properties. For this purpose, epoxy adhesives require highly advanced formulation techniques when applied in transport vehicles as structural adhesives, where they are combined with various additives. Numerous additives have been extensively studied so far, including catalysts, flexibilizers, tougheners, fillers, reactive diluents, and promoters [4,5,6,7,8,9,10,11,12]. The catalysts are mainly imidazoles containing methyl (–CH3) functional groups; these catalysts open the epoxy ring and improve the curing reaction [4]. A flexibilizer and tougheners are added to improve the mechanical properties of epoxy adhesives. Urethane-based polymers are widely used as flexibilizers, which enhance the mechanical properties of epoxy adhesives through phase separation with the epoxy resin [5,6]. The effect of tougheners consisting of core–shell rubber (CSR) particles has recently been studied, and the results suggest that the addition of such tougheners improves the peel strength and impact resistance of the adhesive [7,8]. Reactive diluents are used to reduce the viscosity of epoxy adhesives, and promoters smooth the joint surface, efficiently enhancing the adhesion strength [4]. In addition to variations in the types of additives, formulations can be diversified according to their content, curing conditions, and application temperature, which greatly influence the properties of adhesives. However, the large number of possible formulations and their complexity make quantitative predictions of adhesive properties, or even predictions of their basic properties, challenging. A systematic method for optimizing formulations is needed. As one approach to this problem, machine learning (ML) represents a powerful potential solution. ML is a data analysis method that provides computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed. Unlike conventional statistical data analysis, in which individual analytical models are developed on the basis of each data point, ML learns new data on its own with a model developed by accumulating training experiences from a given data set [13]. Commonly used ML methods include generalized linear regression [14], decision trees [15], random forest [16], support vector machine [17], and artificial neural networks (ANNs) [18]. In particular, ANNs, which are also known as deep learning if the neural network has multiple deep layers, provide the most accurate predictions in a short time from highly disordered data through their high-level algorithms [18]. In recent reports, the use of ANNs in materials science has been successfully demonstrated [19,20,21]. For instance, the tensile shear strength of bonded beechwood was predicted by an ANN model trained using an experimental database [22]. In addition to ANNs being trained with experimental databases, they have also been trained from data sets calculated through density functional theory in applications where they were used to predict redox potentials on the basis of the structure of anode materials for lithium-ion batteries [20] or to screen possible perovskite structures [19]. Therefore, in the present study, an ANN was used as an ML method to predict basic adhesion strength on the basis of the formulation of high-performance epoxy adhesives. Various epoxy adhesive formulations with different contents of basic components were prepared as high-strength structural adhesives. The lap shear strength and impact peel strength of the adhesive with each formulation were obtained experimentally at 25 °C and −40 °C, respectively, to build a database of adhesion strength. The experimental database was first analyzed statistically, and the correlation between variables was examined. The ANN model was built and trained using the examined database and optimized to have high predictability. The optimized ANN model was verified by the linear regression method and errors. Consequently, the adhesion strength was predicted from the content of the critical component, which has been a challenge in this field. Thus, we believe that the approach implemented in the present study will be a cornerstone toward predicting complex formulations of adhesives with targeted properties. ## 2. Materials and Methods ### 2.1. Materials for Formulation Diglycidyl ether bisphenol-A (EEW: 184−190, Kukdo Chemical) as an epoxy resin, dicyandiamide (DICY, Sigma-Aldrich) as a curing agent, 1-cyanoethyl-2-4-metylimidazole (2E4MZ-CNS, Sigma-Aldrich) as a catalyst, and an amino silane-based coupling agent (promoter) were used as received. Hydroxyl-terminated polyurethane (HTPU, Huntsman) and CSR (core–shell rubber) particles (methacrylate-butadiene-styrene (MBS), Rohm & Haas, diameter: 150 nm) were used as a flexibilizer to improve the flexibility and toughness of epoxy blends. As reactive diluent, 1,6-hexanediol diglycidyl ether (HDDGE)), was used. Fumed silica with ~20 nm in diameter as a filler was used to control the thixotropic property of the adhesive. ### 2.2. Mechanical Properties Test Procedure For the preparation of the formulated epoxy system, the epoxy \n\n\nFor each page, provide:\n1. A 300-400 word deep analysis focused on findings relevant to the research question, including:\n   - Key data points, statistics, and numerical findings\n   - Methodology or approach described (if any)\n   - Contradictions or tensions with commonly known information\n   - Confidence assessment for each key finding: HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW\n2. Which STORM perspectives are covered (from: Scientific, Regulatory, Industry, Economic, Public_Health, Historical, Regional, Methodological, Emerging_Trends)\n3. 3-5 specific facts with numbers, dates, or named entities\n4. Any data tables, statistics, or quantitative results (preserve exact numbers)\n5. What new understanding this page adds\n"}],"response_content":"{\n  \"research_notes\": [\n    {\n      \"page_id\": \"page_1\",\n      \"url\": \"https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acsbiomaterials.0c01677\",\n      \"analysis\": \"The provided text is a review article titled Engineering Hydrogel Adhesion for Biomedical Applications via Chemical Design of the Junction, published in ACS Biomaterials Science & Engineering in 2021. It discusses hydrogel adhesion mechanisms, focusing on junction design including covalent, dynamic covalent, and supramolecular interactions rather than specific DVS crosslinked PEI systems. There is no experimental evidence presented herein regarding divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinked polyethylenimine (PEI/BPEI) adhesive coatings on plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide substrates. The review emphasizes wet adhesion challenges due to water content inhibiting interactions, which contrasts significantly with the dry substrate focus of the research question regarding polypropylene and aluminum oxide. Methodology involves reviewing existing literature on hydrogel-tissue and hydrogel-hard surface interfaces to link binding chemistries to emergent adhesive properties. Confidence in the absence of DVS/PEI data is HIGH based on the text provided. The article highlights general principles of adhesion strength tailoring through molecular design, which is conceptually relevant but lacks the specific chemical systems queried. It mentions Young's modulus ranges of approximately 0.01\\u201310 kPa for hydrogels, differing substantially from rigid PEI coatings expected on hard substrates. No molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion are compared to peel strengths here, representing a key methodological gap relative to the research question. The tension lies in the application scope: biomedical hydrogels versus industrial adhesive coatings on plastics and metals. This source establishes the state of hydrogel junction engineering but does not validate the specific DVS/PEI/substrate combination. It suggests adhesion relies on functional group density, a parameter critical for PEI amine groups reacting with DVS, but this is not quantified here for DVS crosslinks. The review indicates that effective adhesion requires overcoming low polymer content density, a challenge distinct from crosslinked PEI layers. Thus, while it provides theoretical background on junction design, it offers no empirical validation for the specific query.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Scientific\",\n        \"Methodological\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Published April 1, 2021\",\n        \"Journal: ACS Biomaterials Science & Engineering\",\n        \"Hydrogel Young's modulus: 0.01-10 kPa\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_data\": \"No specific adhesion strength data tables provided; general modulus range 0.01-10 kPa mentioned.\",\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Provides theoretical context on junction design but confirms lack of specific DVS/PEI experimental data in hydrogel literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"page_id\": \"page_2\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4360/16/5\",\n      \"analysis\": \"This page represents the Table of Contents for Polymers, Volume 16, Issue 5, published by MDPI on March 1, 2024. It lists 159 articles covering diverse polymer science topics such as gas uptake, composite reinforcements, furcellaran immobilization, and PLA composites. None of the visible article titles explicitly mention divinyl sulfone (DVS), polyethylenimine (PEI), plasma-activated polypropylene, or aluminum oxide adhesion studies. The content serves as a bibliographic index rather than a primary data source for the specific research question. Methodology is limited to journal curation and publication metadata display. Confidence that this page lacks direct experimental evidence for the research question is HIGH. The issue includes studies on mechanical behaviors in high-field magnets and structural characterization of biocomposites, indicating a broad scope of polymer mechanics but not the specific adhesive chemistry queried. There are no numerical adhesion strength data points or molecular dynamics predictions visible in this index view. The tension exists between the broad polymer focus of this issue and the niche adhesive interface chemistry required by the research question. While it confirms ongoing research in polymer composites and surface modification, such as PLA scaffolds immersed in SBF, it does not provide the specific DVS/PEI crosslinking data. The publication date of March 2024 indicates current activity in the field, but the specific topic remains uncovered in this snapshot. Specific articles include reviews on gas uptake diffusivity and studies on PEEK/CF-laminated composites, which touch on mechanical strength but not the specific interfacial chemistry of PEI. This page adds understanding of the current publication landscape in polymer science, highlighting that while adhesion and composites are active areas, the specific DVS/PEI system is not a headline topic in this specific issue. It serves as a negative control for literature searching, confirming that recent high-volume polymer issues do not prioritize this specific crosslinking chemistry. The lack of relevant titles suggests the research topic may be specialized or published in different journals.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Scientific\",\n        \"Industry\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Publication Date: March 1, 2024\",\n        \"Journal: Polymers\",\n        \"Issue contains 159 articles\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_data\": \"159 articles listed in Volume 16, Issue 5.\",\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Confirms DVS/PEI adhesion is not a prominent topic in recent major polymer journal issues as of early 2024.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"page_id\": \"page_3\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.mdpi.com/2079-4991/11/4/872\",\n      \"analysis\": \"The article Prediction of Lap Shear Strength and Impact Peel Strength of Epoxy Adhesive by Machine Learning Approach (Nanomaterials, 2021) investigates epoxy adhesives using artificial neural networks (ANN). It does not contain experimental evidence for DVS crosslinked PEI on plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The study focuses on epoxy resin based on bisphenol-A, dicyandiamide curing agents, and silane coupling agents. Methodology involves experimental testing of lap shear strength at 25\\u00b0C and impact peel strength at \\u221240\\u00b0C, followed by ML modeling to predict formulation outcomes. Confidence that this does not address the DVS/PEI query is HIGH. Key data includes mentions of RMSE and R2 values for model optimization, though exact numbers are not fully visible in the snippet provided. The study compares machine learning predictions against experimental databases, contrasting with the research question's focus on molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work. Tensions arise in the predictive approach: ML statistical correlation versus physics-based MD simulation required by the query. The paper highlights catalyst and flexibilizer content as high-correlation variables for strength, differing from PEI crosslinking density. It confirms lap shear and peel strength are standard metrics, relevant to the query's metrics, but the chemistry differs fundamentally (epoxy vs. PEI/DVS). No plasma activation or Al2O3 substrates are specified in the snippet, though structural adhesives often bond metals. This adds understanding that adhesion strength prediction is an active computational field, but current prominent methods utilize ML on formulation data rather than MD on single-bond work for these specific systems. It underscores the gap between formulation optimization and fundamental bond energy prediction. Additives like core\\u2013shell rubber particles are used for toughness, unlike DVS crosslinking. The study demonstrates that component content drives strength, implying PEI concentration would be critical in the query's system, but no direct comparison exists.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Scientific\",\n        \"Methodological\",\n        \"Industry\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Published 30 March 2021\",\n        \"Journal: Nanomaterials\",\n        \"Test temperatures: 25\\u00b0C and -40\\u00b0C\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_data\": \"Mentions RMSE and R2 values for ANN model; specific numbers not visible in snippet.\",\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Highlights ML usage for epoxy adhesion prediction, contrasting with the MD approach sought for PEI/DVS systems.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}","response_reasoning":"Thinking Process:\n\n1.  **Analyze the Request:**\n    *   **Role:** Research analyst reading web pages for a deep research project.\n    *   **Research Question:** What experimental evidence exists for divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinked polyethylenimine (PEI/BPEI) adhesive coatings on plasma-activated polypropylene and aluminum oxide substrates, and how do measured peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths compare with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion?\n    *   **Input:** 3 web pages (content provided).\n    *   **Output Format:** Valid JSON only. No prose, no markdown, no code fences.\n    *   **Task:** Create a research note for *each* page (3 notes total) containing:\n        1.  300-400 word deep analysis (findings relevant to research question, data points, methodology, contradictions, confidence).\n        2.  STORM perspectives covered.\n        3.  3-5 specific facts (numbers, dates, entities).\n        4.  Data tables/statistics/quantitative results (exact numbers).\n        5.  New understanding added.\n    *   **Constraint:** MUST respond with valid JSON only.\n\n2.  **Analyze the Input Pages:**\n\n    *   **Page 1:** \"Engineering Hydrogel Adhesion for Biomedical Applications via Chemical Design of the Junction\" (ACS Biomaterials Science & Engineering, 2021).\n        *   *Content:* Review article about hydrogel adhesion, junction design, biomedical applications. Mentions hydrogel adhesion to hard/dry surfaces. Discusses covalent, dynamic covalent, supramolecular interactions.\n        *   *Relevance to Research Question:* The research question asks about DVS crosslinked PEI/BPEI on plasma-activated PP and Al2O3. This page is a general review on hydrogel adhesion. It does *not* mention DVS, PEI, BPEI, plasma-activated polypropylene, aluminum oxide, or molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion in the provided text snippet. It discusses general principles (junction design, wet adhesion).\n        *   *Assessment:* Low relevance to the specific chemical system (DVS/PEI) and substrates (PP/Al2O3) in the research question. It provides context on hydrogel adhesion mechanisms but no specific experimental evidence for the query.\n\n    *   **Page 2:** \"Polymers, Volume 16, Issue 5 (March-1 2024) – 159 articles - MDPI\" (Journal Issue Page).\n        *   *Content:* Table of contents for Polymers Vol 16 Issue 5. Lists titles of articles (e.g., Gas Uptake, Polymer-Based Composite Reinforcements, Furcellaran, Y-Shaped Polymer Brushes, PLA/B-TCP, Dog Wool, PEEK/CF).\n        *   *Relevance to Research Question:* None of the visible titles mention DVS, PEI, plasma-activated PP, Al2O3, or molecular dynamics of adhesion. It's a journal index page.\n        *   *Assessment:* Negligible relevance. No specific data regarding the research question.\n\n    *   **Page 3:** \"Prediction of Lap Shear Strength and Impact Peel Strength of Epoxy Adhesive by Machine Learning Approach\" (Nanomaterials, 2021).\n        *   *Content:* Article about using ANN/ML to predict lap shear and impact peel strength of *epoxy* adhesives. Mentions components like DICY, imidazoles, silane coupling agents. Tests at 25°C and -40°C.\n        *   *Relevance to Research Question:* The research question asks about DVS crosslinked PEI/BPEI on PP/Al2O3. This paper is about *epoxy* adhesives (bisphenol-A, dicyandiamide) on structural joints (likely metal/composite, unspecified but typical for structural epoxy). It discusses lap shear and peel strength prediction via ML, not molecular dynamics of single-bond work of adhesion. It does not mention DVS, PEI, plasma activation, or Al2O3 specifically in the context of the query.\n        *   *Assessment:* Low relevance to the specific chemical system. It provides methodology on adhesion strength prediction (ML vs experimental) but not the specific DVS/PEI system or MD predictions.\n\n3.  **Drafting the Research Notes (Mental Check):**\n    *   *Challenge:* The provided pages do *not* contain the specific information requested in the research question (DVS/PEI on plasma-activated PP/Al2O3 with MD comparisons). I must accurately report what *is* there while noting the lack of specific evidence for the query. I cannot hallucinate data.\n    *   *Strategy:* For each page, analyze the content provided. State clearly that specific evidence for DVS/PEI/PP/Al2O3 is absent, but note relevant general adhesion concepts (hydrogel junctions, epoxy lap shear prediction) that might contextualize the broader field.\n    *   *Word Count:* 300-400 words per analysis section.\n    *   *JSON Structure:* Needs to be a single JSON object containing an array of notes or keys for each page. The prompt says \"create a research note for each\". I will structure the JSON as an object with keys `page_1`, `page_2`, `page_3` or an array `notes`. Let's use an array `notes` for clarity, or specific keys. Given the strict JSON requirement, I'll use a structured object like `{\"research_notes\": [...]}`.\n    *   *Constraint Check:* \"No prose, no markdown, no code fences — just the JSON object.\" This means the entire output must be parseable JSON. I need to be careful with newlines and quotes within the JSON strings.\n\n4.  **Drafting Content (Iterative refinement for word count and accuracy):**\n\n    *   *Page 1 (ACS Review):* Focus on hydrogel adhesion mechanisms. Note absence of DVS/PEI. Mention junction design concepts.\n    *   *Page 2 (MDPI Index):* Focus on it being a TOC. Note absence of relev