e DVS/PEI query is HIGH. Key data includes RMSE and R2 values for model optimization, though exact numbers are not fully visible in the snippet. The study compares machine learning predictions against experimental databases, contrasting with the research question's focus on molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work. Tensions arise in the predictive approach: ML statistical correlation versus physics-based MD simulation. The paper highlights catalyst and flexibilizer content as high-correlation variables for strength. It confirms lap shear and peel strength are standard metrics, relevant to the query's metrics, but the chemistry differs fundamentally (epoxy vs. PEI/DVS). No plasma activation or Al2O3 substrates are specified in the snippet. This adds understanding that adhesion strength prediction is an active computational field, but current prominent methods utilize ML on formulation data rather than MD on single-bond work for these specific systems. It underscores the gap between formulation optimization and fundamental bond energy prediction.\n\n    *   *Word Count Check:*\n        *   Page 1: ~200 words. Need to expand. I will elaborate more on the implications of hydrogel vs dry coating and the specific lack of MD data.\n        *   Page 2: ~200 words. Need to expand on the specific titles and what they imply about the field's direction vs the query.\n        *   Page 3: ~200 words. Need to expand on the ML vs MD distinction and the specific temperature conditions.\n\n    *   *Expansion Strategy:* I will elaborate on the methodological implications and the specific chemical differences to ensure I hit the 300-400 word range without lying.\n\n    *   *JSON Safety:* I must ensure no unescaped newlines or quotes. I will write the text as a single continuous string with `\\n` for breaks if needed, but JSON strings can contain `\\n`. I will keep paragraphs separated by `\\n\\n`.\n\n    *   *Final Plan:* Construct the JSON structure. Ensure all fields are pr