posites, indicating a broad scope of polymer mechanics but not the specific adhesive chemistry queried. There are no numerical adhesion strength data points or molecular dynamics predictions visible in this index view. The tension exists between the broad polymer focus of this issue and the niche adhesive interface chemistry required by the research question. While it confirms ongoing research in polymer composites and surface modification, such as PLA scaffolds immersed in SBF, it does not provide the specific DVS/PEI crosslinking data. The publication date of March 2024 indicates current activity in the field, but the specific topic remains uncovered in this snapshot. Specific articles include reviews on gas uptake diffusivity and studies on PEEK/CF-laminated composites, which touch on mechanical strength but not the specific interfacial chemistry of PEI. This page adds understanding of the current publication landscape in polymer science, highlighting that while adhesion and composites are active areas, the specific DVS/PEI system is not a headline topic in this specific issue. It serves as a negative control for literature searching, confirming that recent high-volume polymer issues do not prioritize this specific crosslinking chemistry. The lack of relevant titles suggests the research topic may be specialized or published in different journals.\n\n    *   Page 3: The article \"Prediction of Lap Shear Strength and Impact Peel Strength of Epoxy Adhesive by Machine Learning Approach\" (Nanomaterials, 2021) investigates epoxy adhesives using artificial neural networks (ANN). It does not contain experimental evidence for DVS crosslinked PEI on plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The study focuses on epoxy resin based on bisphenol-A, dicyandiamide curing agents, and silane coupling agents. Methodology involves experimental testing of lap shear strength at 25°C and impact peel strength at −40°C, followed by ML modeling to predict formulation outcomes. C