-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/file_download.svg) ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/pdf/polymers-17-00726.pdf)Download PDF * ![Collections icon](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/pd-medc-pmc-cloudpmc-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/action-bookmark-full.svg) ![Collections icon](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/pd-medc-pmc-cloudpmc-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/action-bookmark-empty.svg) Add to Collections * ![Cite icon](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/pd-medc-pmc-cloudpmc-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/format_quote.svg) Cite * ![Show article permalink icon](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/pd-medc-pmc-cloudpmc-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/share.svg) Permalink ## PERMALINK ![Copy icon](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/pd-medc-pmc-cloudpmc-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/content_copy.svg) Copy ![Open article navigation icon](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/pd-medc-pmc-cloudpmc-viewer/production/a2b04810/var/data/static/img/list.svg) As a library, NLM provides access to scientific literature. Inclusion in an NLM database does not imply endorsement of, or agreement with, the contents by NLM or the National Institutes of Health. Learn more: [PMC Disclaimer](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/about/disclaimer/) | [ PMC Copyright Notice ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/about/copyright/) ![Polymers logo](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/banners/logo-polymers.png) Polymers (Basel) . 2025 Mar 10;17(6):726. doi: [10.3390/polym17060726](https://doi.org/10.3390/polym17060726) * [Search in PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/?term=\"Polymers%20\\(Basel\\)\"\\[jour\\]) * [Search in PubMed](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Polymers%20\\(Basel\\)\"\\[jour\\]) * [View in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=\"Polymers%20\\(Basel\\)\"\\[Title%20Abbreviation\\]) * [Add to search](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/?term=\"Polymers%20\\(Basel\\)\"\\[jour\\]) # Enhancement of Polypropylene Bonding Through Plasma–Ultrasonic Treatment [Hui Wang](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Wang%20H\"\\[Author\\]) ### Hui Wang 1Hubei Key Laboratory of Advanced Technology for Automotive Components, Wuhan University of Technology, Wuhan 430070, China; huiwang@whut.edu.cn (H.W.); ych1049732204558@whut.edu.cn (C.Y.) 2Hubei Longzhong Laboratory, Xiangyang 441000, China 3Hubei Collaborative Innovation Center for Automotive Components Technology, Wuhan 430070, China Conceptualization Find articles by [Hui Wang](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Wang%20H\"\\[Author\\]) 1,2,3, [Chuhao Yang](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Yang%20C\"\\[Author\\]) ### Chuhao Yang 1Hubei Key Laboratory of Advanced Technology for Automotive Components, Wuhan University of Technology, Wuhan 430070, China; huiwang@whut.edu.cn (H.W.); ych1049732204558@whut.edu.cn (C.Y.) 3Hubei Collaborative Innovation Center for Automotive Components Technology, Wuhan 430070, China Find articles by [Chuhao Yang](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Yang%20C\"\\[Author\\]) 1,3, [Limei He](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"He%20L\"\\[Author\\]) ### Limei He 4Guangxi Laboratory of New Energy Automobile, SAIC GM Wuling Automobile Co., Ltd., Liuzhou 545001, China; binbin.yu@sgmw.com.cn (B.Y.); xiaobin.zhao@sgmw.com.cn (X.Z.); zongbin.huang@sgmw.com.cn (Z.H.) Find articles by [Limei He](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"He%20L\"\\[Author\\]) 4,*, [Binbin Yu](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Yu%20B\"\\[Author\\]) ### Binbin Yu 4Guangxi Laboratory of New Energy Automobile, SAIC GM Wuling Automobile Co., Ltd., Liuzhou 545001, China; binbin.yu@sgmw.com.cn (B.Y.); xiaobin.zhao@sgmw.com.cn (X.Z.); zongbin.huang@sgmw.com.cn (Z.H.) Find articles by [Binbin Yu](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Yu%20B\"\\[Author\\]) 4, [Xiaobin Zhao](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Zhao%20X\"\\[Author\\]) ### Xiaobin Zhao 4Guangxi Laboratory of New Energy Automobile, SAIC GM Wuling Automobile Co., Ltd., Liuzhou 545001, China; binbin.yu@sgmw.com.cn (B.Y.); xiaobin.zhao@sgmw.com.cn (X.Z.); zongbin.huang@sgmw.com.cn (Z.H.) Find articles by [Xiaobin Zhao](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Zhao%20X\"\\[Author\\]) 4, [Zongbin Huang](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Huang%20Z\"\\[Author\\]) ### Zongbin Huang 4Guangxi Laboratory of New Energy Automobile, SAIC GM Wuling Automobile Co., Ltd., Liuzhou 545001, China; binbin.yu@sgmw.com.cn (B.Y.); xiaobin.zhao@sgmw.com.cn (X.Z.); zongbin.huang@sgmw.com.cn (Z.H.) Find articles by [Zongbin Huang](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=\"Huang%20Z\"\\[Author\\]) 4 Editor: Choon-Sang Park * Author information * Article notes * Copyright and License information 1Hubei Key Laboratory of Advanced Technology for Automotive Components, Wuhan University of Technology, Wuhan 430070, China; huiwang@whut.edu.cn (H.W.); ych1049732204558@whut.edu.cn (C.Y.) 2Hubei Longzhong Laboratory, Xiangyang 441000, China 3Hubei Collaborative Innovation Center for Automotive Components Technology, Wuhan 430070, China 4Guangxi Laboratory of New Energy Automobile, SAIC GM Wuling Automobile Co., Ltd., Liuzhou 545001, China; binbin.yu@sgmw.com.cn (B.Y.); xiaobin.zhao@sgmw.com.cn (X.Z.); zongbin.huang@sgmw.com.cn (Z.H.) * Correspondence: limei.he@sgmw.com.cn #### Roles **Hui Wang** : Conceptualization **Choon-Sang Park** : Academic Editor Received 2025 Feb 5; Revised 2025 Mar 3; Accepted 2025 Mar 5; Collection date 2025 Mar. © 2025 by the authors. Licensee MDPI, Basel, Switzerland. This article is an open access article distributed under the terms and conditions of the Creative Commons Attribution (CC BY) license ( ). [PMC Copyright notice](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/about/copyright/) PMCID: PMC11945717 PMID: [40292546](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40292546/) ## Abstract In response to the issue of the insufficient adhesion strength of polypropylene materials, a plasma–ultrasonic treatment is proposed. Plasma treatment is first conducted to activate the polypropylene adherends, and then ultrasonic vibration is applied to the adhesive to facilitate the interface contact, enhancing the bonding performance of polypropylene. The shear strength of the test specimens was assessed using single-lap shear tests. The bonding samples were characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS), contact angle, and infrared analysis to explore the bonding mechanism of plasma–ultrasonic treatment. The results show that compared to untreated polypropylene specimens, the plasma treatment process increased the shear strength of the polypropylene specimens by 370.3%, and the addition of ultrasonic-assisted technology further increased the shear strength of the polypropylene specimens by 10.6%. The coefficient of variation decreased from 0.53 in the untreated sample to 0.32 for the plasma–ultrasonic treatment, enhancing the stability of adhesion. Plasma treatment introduces active groups, such as hydroxyl groups, onto the surface of polypropylene and increases the surface roughness of polypropylene. Ultrasonic treatment promotes the penetration of adhesive microstructures on the surface of polypropylene, enhancing the anchoring effect of the adhesive, thereby improving bonding performance. Furthermore, through molecular dynamics analysis, compared to the untreated polypropylene bonding system, the bonding energy of the bonding system under the plasma–ultrasonic treatment was increased by 57%, effectively enhancing the shear strength of polypropylene bonding. Plasma–ultrasonic treatment can effectively improve the bonding strength of polypropylene, providing a new idea for the study of polymer bonding. **Keywords:** polypropylene bonding, plasma–ultrasonic treatment, molecular dynamics ## 1. Introduction Polypropylene (PP) is a thermoplastic resin made from the polymerization of propylene monomers and characterized by excellent chemical resistance, heat resistance, high strength, and toughness [[1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B1-polymers-17-00726),[2](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B2-polymers-17-00726)]. In the automotive field, PP is commonly used for door trim, bumpers, side panels, and other components due to its durability, wear resistance, and ease of maintenance [[3](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B3-polymers-17-00726)]. With the development needs of automotive lightweighting, plastic tailgates use PP materials for both inner and outer panels and are bonded together through adhesive processes. Due to the challenges in controlling the energy during welding, the poor joint strength, and the fact that welding can cause some degree of damage to the components, the automotive tailgate is typically joined using adhesive bonding. However, the low surface energy, high chemical inertness, low surface roughness, and the presence of weak boundary layers of PP collectively lead to difficulties in bonding and insufficient strength [[4](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B4-polymers-17-00726)]. Solving these problems typically requires special adhesives and surface treatment technologies to improve the bonding performance of PP plastics. Currently, the physical methods for modification mainly include sanding and sandblasting [[5](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B5-polymers-17-00726),[6](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B6-polymers-17-00726)]. Chemical methods [[7](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B7-polymers-17-00726)] include surface treatments such as plasma treatment [[8](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B8-polymers-17-00726),[9](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B9-polymers-17-00726)], coupling agent treatment [[10](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B10-polymers-17-00726)], and anodization [[11](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B11-polymers-17-00726)]. Mandolfino et al. [[12](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B12-polymers-17-00726)] demonstrated the improvement of adhesion performance of polyethylene treated with plasma in terms of wettability, evaluated by contact angle measurement and the lap shear strength of adhesive joints achieved using treated surfaces. Mandolfino et al. [[13](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B13-polymers-17-00726)] also used plasma to treat the polypropylene surface, and the results showed that plasma treatment increased the surface roughness of polypropylene, and more oxygen-containing polar groups were introduced into the treated polypropylene surface, which enhanced the hydrophilicity and chemical activity of the surface and helped to improve the bonding performance. Sanchis et al. [[14](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B14-polymers-17-00726)] treated polyethylene film with plasma, greatly increasing the surface energy value of polar components, indicating surface activation due to the generation of polar groups (mainly =CO, -COOH, and -OH groups) and also revealed a slight increase in surface roughness due to surface etching. Hao Du et al. [[15](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/#B15-polymers-17-00726)] studied the interaction between O or OH radicals and the PP surface. The high reactivity of the O radical and the high efficiency of hydrogen atom extraction make it show higher efficiency in the surface modification, which is helpful to further improve the surface modification effect of polypropylene. The plasma treatment process increased the surface roughness of PP and changed the chemical properties of the PP surface. However, d\n\n--- PAGE: Relationship between structure and cytocompatibility of divinyl ... ---\nURL: https://hero.epa.gov/reference/4690362/\nCONTENT:\nRelationship between structure and cytocompatibility of divinyl sulfone cross-linked hyaluronic acid An official website of the United States government Here’s how you know Here’s how you know Official websites use .gov A .gov website belongs to an official government organization in the United States. Secure .gov websites use HTTPS A lock ( Lock A locked padlock ) or https:// means you’ve safely connected to the .gov website. Share sensitive information only on official, secure websites. Menu Search Search Primary navigation Environmental Topics Laws & Regulations Report a Violation About EPA HERO About FAQ Risk Assessment Transparency & Integrity Contact Us Report an Issue Browse Search HERO Projects Login Home References Lai JY 2014 Please check your network connection and refresh this page Relationship between structure and cytocompatibility of divinyl sulfone cross-linked hyaluronic acid Lai, JY HERO ID 4690362 Reference Type Journal Article Year 2014 Language English PMID 24299766 Feedback HERO ID 4690362 In Press No Year 2014 Title Relationship between structure and cytocompatibility of divinyl sulfone cross-linked hyaluronic acid Authors Lai, JY Journal Carbohydrate Polymers Volume 101 Page Numbers 203-212 Abstract Hyaluronic acid (HA), a carbohydrate polymer naturally found in the eye, has been chemically modified by cross-linking to enhance its performance as a drug carrier. Although the treatment of HA with divinyl sulfone (DVS) is reported, the effects of cross-linker concentration on the biomaterial-mediated retinal pigment epithelial (RPE) cellular responses are yet to be investigated. This paper explores, for the first time, the relationship between molecular structure and cytocompatibility of HA hydrogels cross-linked with DVS of varying concentrations (0-100mM). The results showed that with increasing DVS concentration, the sulfur content and sulfonyl-bis-ethyl cross-link amount are increased and the mechanical stability and resistance against enzymatic degradation are enhanced, indicating the crucial role of cross-linker in the alteration of structure and property of this polysaccharide biomaterial. The cell viability, pro-inflammatory gene and cytokine expression, and glutamate uptake were suggested to be indicative of cytocompatibility and found to be strongly dependent on the cross-linker concentration. Doi 10.1016/j.carbpol.2013.09.060 Pmid 24299766 Wosid WOS:000330494800025 Url https://search.proquest.com/docview/2000236744?accountid=171501 Is Certified Translation No Dupe Override No Is Public Yes Language Text English Keyword cell viability; crosslinking; cytokines; drug carriers; epithelium; glutamic acid; hyaluronic acid; hydrocolloids; polymers; Internet resource Relationship(s) Tags No Tags Found Contact Us for questions about HERO. Got feedback? Report an Issue here . Last updated on January 23, 2026 Discover. Accessibility Statement Budget & Performance Contracting EPA www Web Snapshots Grants No FEAR Act Data Privacy Privacy and Security Notice Connect. Data.gov Exit EPA's Website Inspector General Jobs Newsroom Open Government Regulations.gov Subscribe USA.gov White House Ask. Contact EPA EPA Disclaimers Hotlines FOIA Requests Frequent Questions Follow.\n\n\nFor each page, provide:\n1. A 300-400 word deep analysis focused on findings relevant to the research question, including:\n   - Key data points, statistics, and numerical findings\n   - Methodology or approach described (if any)\n   - Contradictions or tensions with commonly known information\n   - Confidence assessment for each key finding: HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW\n2. Which STORM perspectives are covered (from: Scientific, Regulatory, Industry, Economic, Public_Health, Historical, Regional, Methodological, Emerging_Trends)\n3. 3-5 specific facts with numbers, dates, or named entities\n4. Any data tables, statistics, or quantitative results (preserve exact numbers)\n5. What new understanding this page adds\n"}],"response_content":"{\n  \"research_notes\": [\n    {\n      \"page_url\": \"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/229902264_Plasma-induced_surface_modification_and_adhesion_enhancement_of_polypropylene_surface\",\n      \"analysis\": \"This page represents a significant access barrier within the literature review process for divinyl sulfone crosslinked polyethylenimine adhesive coatings. The content provided is solely a security verification checkpoint from ResearchGate, indicating that automated scraping or network activity triggered a defense mechanism. Consequently, no experimental evidence regarding plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide substrates could be extracted from this specific URL. The absence of data here highlights a common challenge in aggregating proprietary or hosted academic PDFs where full-text access is restricted behind authentication walls. For the research question concerning measured peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths, this source contributes zero quantitative values. The methodology described is non-existent beyond the network handshake. There are no contradictions to existing knowledge because no scientific claims are made. The confidence assessment for any finding related to the research question is effectively zero, classified as LOW, because the source failed to deliver the promised title content regarding plasma-induced surface modification. This failure necessitates reliance on alternative open-access repositories like PMC or publisher direct links to verify claims about polyethylenimine modifications. The inability to access this specific publication prevents cross-verification of plasma treatment protocols that might otherwise complement the divinyl sulfone crosslinking data found in other contexts. Researchers must note that while the title suggests relevance to polypropylene surface adhesion enhancement, the actual data remains obscured. This underscores the importance of utilizing multiple database sources when investigating niche polymer adhesive formulations where full-text availability varies significantly across hosting platforms. Furthermore, the lack of access prevents any comparison between macroscopic adhesion measurements and molecular dynamics predictions, which is a core component of the primary research inquiry. Without the text, we cannot determine if this study utilized divinyl sulfone or alternative crosslinkers, leaving a gap in the comprehensive mapping of chemical modifications available for polypropylene bonding enhancement strategies in current literature. The copyright notice indicates a range from 2008 to 2026, suggesting long-term hosting but current access restriction.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Methodological\",\n        \"Scientific\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"URL blocked by security check\",\n        \"ResearchGate GmbH copyright 2008-2026\",\n        \"Client IP 216.232.201.117 detected\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_results\": [],\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Confirms that specific literature on plasma-induced polypropylene modification may be inaccessible via automated tools, requiring manual verification or alternative database sourcing to validate DVS/PEI adhesive claims.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"page_url\": \"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/\",\n      \"analysis\": \"This article provides substantial data on polypropylene bonding enhancement but lacks specific mention of divinyl sulfone or polyethylenimine. The study utilizes plasma-ultrasonic treatment to improve adhesion, reporting a shear strength increase of 370.3% compared to untreated specimens. The addition of ultrasonic assistance further increased strength by 10.6%. Molecular dynamics analysis indicated a 57% increase in bonding energy for the treated system. While the substrate matches the research question (polypropylene), the adhesive chemistry differs from the DVS/PEI focus. The methodology includes single-lap shear tests, SEM, EDS, contact angle, and infrared analysis. There are no contradictions with general plasma treatment literature, which consistently shows surface activation improves bonding. Confidence for the plasma data is HIGH, but confidence for relevance to DVS/PEI specific mechanisms is LOW. The study confirms plasma activation introduces hydroxyl groups and increases roughness, which are mechanisms likely relevant to any adhesive system including DVS/PEI. However, without explicit DVS mention, direct comparison of lap-shear strengths to MD predictions of single-bond work of adhesion for DVS/PEI is not possible using this text alone. The MD results here are system-specific to the plasma-ultrasonic interface rather than a specific crosslinker bond energy. This source is valuable for establishing baseline plasma treatment efficacy on PP but requires supplementation with chemistry-specific studies to address the divinyl sulfone crosslinking aspect of the research question. The coefficient of variation decreased from 0.53 to 0.32, indicating improved stability, a metric relevant for industrial application of any adhesive coating system. The automotive context highlights the practical need for such bonding in tailgates and panels, suggesting industrial relevance. The absence of aluminum oxide substrates limits the scope regarding multi-material bonding. The molecular dynamics analysis here focuses on bonding energy of the system rather than single-bond work of adhesion, creating a definitional gap when comparing to the research question's specific requirement for single-bond predictions. This distinction is critical for validating theoretical models against experimental peel or shear strengths. Authors include Hui Wang from Wuhan University of Technology.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Scientific\",\n        \"Industry\",\n        \"Methodological\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Published 2025 Mar 10 in Polymers (Basel)\",\n        \"Authors include Hui Wang and Chuhao Yang\",\n        \"PMCID: PMC11945717\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_results\": [\n        \"Shear strength increased by 370.3%\",\n        \"Ultrasonic assistance increased strength by 10.6%\",\n        \"Bonding energy increased by 57%\",\n        \"Coefficient of variation decreased from 0.53 to 0.32\"\n      ],\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Establishes that plasma-ultrasonic treatment significantly boosts PP adhesion and bonding energy via MD, but does not confirm DVS/PEI specific chemistry or single-bond work of adhesion correlations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"page_url\": \"https://hero.epa.gov/reference/4690362/\",\n      \"analysis\": \"This reference details divinyl sulfone crosslinking but applies it to hyaluronic acid rather than polyethylenimine. The study investigates cytocompatibility and structural changes with DVS concentrations ranging from 0 to 100 mM. It confirms DVS increases sulfur content and mechanical stability in hydrogels. However, it does not address adhesive coatings on polypropylene or aluminum oxide. There is no data on peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths, nor are there molecular dynamics predictions of bond work. The methodology focuses on biological responses like cell viability and cytokine expression. Confidence for DVS chemistry is HIGH, but confidence for adhesive performance data is LOW. This source confirms DVS is a viable crosslinker for polymers, supporting the chemical feasibility aspect of the research question, but fails to provide the mechanical adhesion data required. The context is biomedical drug carriers, which differs significantly from industrial adhesive coatings. There are no contradictions, but the application domain mismatch limits utility. The study notes enzymatic degradation resistance enhances with crosslinker concentration, a property potentially relevant to adhesive durability but not explicitly tested here. The lack of substrate information (PP or Al2O3) means this source cannot contribute to the substrate activation component of the research question. It serves primarily as evidence that DVS crosslinking quantification is possible via sulfur content analysis. The absence of MD simulations in this biological context further widens the gap between available literature and the specific computational-experimental comparison sought in the research question. Researchers must look for industrial polymer literature rather than biomedical hydrogel studies to find the specific PEI/DVS adhesion metrics. The specific range of 0 to 100 mM DVS provides a benchmark for crosslinker concentration effects, though mechanical stability here refers to hydrogel integrity rather than interfacial adhesion strength. The focus on retinal pigment epithelial cellular responses underscores the biocompatibility focus, contrasting with the structural bonding focus of the research question. This divergence suggests that while DVS chemistry is well-documented in biomedicine, its application in high-strength structural adhesives on activated metals or plastics requires distinct investigation parameters not covered in this cytocompatibility study. The EPA HERO ID is 4690362.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Scientific\",\n        \"Public_Health\",\n        \"Regulatory\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Published 2014 in Carbohydrate Polymers\",\n        \"Author Lai, JY\",\n        \"EPA HERO ID 4690362\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_results\": [\n        \"DVS concentrations 0-100 mM\",\n        \"PMID 24299766\",\n        \"Volume 101 Page Numbers 203-212\"\n      ],\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Validates DVS as a crosslinker in polymer systems but highlights a domain gap between biomedical hydrogel stability and industrial adhesive shear strength on activated substrates.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}","response_reasoning":"Thinking Process:\n\n1.  **Analyze the Request:**\n    *   **Role:** Research Analyst.\n    *   **Task:** Read 3 provided web pages and create a research note for each.\n    *   **Research Question:** What experimental evidence exists for divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinked polyethylenimine (PEI/BPEI) adhesive coatings on plasma-activated polypropylene and aluminum oxide substrates, and how do measured peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths compare with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion?\n    *   **Output Format:** Valid JSON only. No prose, no markdown, no code fences.\n    *   **Content Requirements per Page:**\n        1.  300-400 word deep analysis (findings, data, methodology, contradictions, confidence).\n        2.  STORM perspectives covered.\n        3.  3-5 specific facts (numbers, dates, entities).\n        4.  Data tables/statistics/quantitative results (exact numbers).\n        5.  New understanding added.\n    *   **Constraint:** MUST respond with valid JSON only.\n\n2.  **Analyze the Input Pages:**\n\n    *   **Page 1:** `https://www.researchgate.net/publication/229902264_Plasma-induced_surface_modification_and_adhesion_enhancement_of_polypropylene_surface`\n        *   **Content:** Security check page (\"We've detected unusual activity...\"). No actual scientific content.\n        *   **Relevance to Research Question:** None. Cannot extract data on DVS, PEI, PP, Al2O3, adhesion strengths, or MD predictions.\n        *   **Action:** Note the lack of content due to access barrier.\n\n    *   **Page 2:** `https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945717/`\n        *   **Title:** Enhancement of Polypropylene Bonding Through Plasma–Ultrasonic Treatment.\n        *   **Content:** Abstract and Introduction visible. Discusses Plasma-Ultrasonic treatment on Polypropylene (PP).\n        *   **Relevance to Research Question:**\n            *   *Substrate:* Polypropylene (Yes).\n            *   *Treatment:* Plasma (Yes).\n            *   *Adhesive/Crosslinker:* Mentions \"adhesive\" generally, but *does not* specify Divinyl Sulfone (DVS) or Polyethylenimine (PEI/BPEI). It mentions plasma-ultrasonic treatment.\n            *   *Comparison:* Mentions Molecular Dynamics (MD) analysis comparing bonding energy (increased by 57%).\n            *   *Gap:* Does not mention DVS or PEI. Does not mention Aluminum Oxide.\n        *   **Action:** Extract relevant PP/Plasma/MD data but note the absence of DVS/PEI specific info.\n\n    *   **Page 3:** `https://hero.epa.gov/reference/4690362/`\n        *   **Title:** Relationship between structure and cytocompatibility of divinyl sulfone cross-linked hyaluronic acid.\n        *   **Content:** Metadata/Abstract snippet. Discusses DVS cross-linked *Hyaluronic Acid (HA)*, not PEI.\n        *   **Relevance to Research Question:**\n            *   *Crosslinker:* Divinyl Sulfone (DVS) (Yes).\n            *   *Polymer:* Hyaluronic Acid (HA), *not* Polyethylenimine (PEI).\n            *   *Substrate:* Not specified (biomaterial/drug carrier context).\n            *   *Adhesion/MD:* No adhesion strength or MD predictions mentioned.\n        *   **Action:** Note the DVS connection but clarify the polymer mismatch (HA vs PEI) and lack of adhesion/MD data.\n\n3.  **Drafting the Content (Mental or Scratchpad):**\n\n    *   *Constraint Check:* The output must be valid JSON. I need to structure the three notes within a JSON object.\n    *   *Word Count:* Each analysis needs to be 300-400 words. This is tight for JSON strings (need to escape newlines). I will write the text carefully to meet the count.\n    *   *Page 1 Analysis:* Focus on the failure to access. State that no evidence was found due to security block. Confidence LOW for any findings because there are none.\n    *   *Page 2 Analysis:* Focus on PP plasma treatment. Shear strength increased 370.3%. Ultrasonic added 10.6%. MD showed 57% bonding energy increase. Note absence of DVS/PEI. Confidence HIGH for the data present, LOW for relevance to specific DVS/PEI question.\n    *   *Page 3 Analysis:* Focus on DVS crosslinking. But it's HA, not PEI. No adhesion data. Confidence HIGH for DVS/HA link, LOW for relevance to adhesive coatings on PP/Al2O3.\n\n    *   *Word Count Strategy:* I need to ensure each analysis string is between 300 and 400 words. I will draft them to be verbose enough to hit the minimum while staying under the max.\n    *   *JSON Structure:* I'll create an object with a key \"research_notes\" containing an array of 3 objects, one for each page. Each object will have the required fields.\n\n    *   *Refining Word Count:*\n        *   Drafting Page 1: Need to expand on the implication of the security block for research validity.\n        *   Drafting Page 2: Expand on the methodology (SEM, EDS, contact angle) and the specific MD implications relative to the research question (even if negative).\n        *   Drafting Page 3: Expand on the DVS chemistry context and why HA differs from PEI in adhesion contexts.\n\n    *   *STORM Perspectives:* Select from the provided list.\n    *   *Facts:* Extract specific numbers.\n    *   *Data Tables:* Extract exact numbers.\n    *   *New Understanding:* Summarize the gap analysis.\n\n    *   *Critical Check:* The prompt asks for \"valid JSON only. No prose, no markdown, no code fences\". I must ensure the output starts with `{` and ends with `}`. I must escape quotes and newlines within the strings.\n\n    *   *Word Count Verification:* I will count words carefully during drafting.\n        *   Page 1 Target: ~350 words.\n        *   Page 2 Target: ~350 words.\n        *   Page 3 Target: ~350 words.\n\n    *   *Wait, one major constraint:* \"No prose, no markdown, no code fences — just the JSON object.\"\n    *   *Another constraint:* \"For each page, provide: 1. A 300-400 word deep analysis...\"\n    *   *Challenge:* Writing exactly 300-400 words inside a JSON string value is difficult to verify precisely without a tool, but I will aim for substantial paragraphs. I need to make sure I don't accidentally drop below 300. I will write dense paragraphs.\n\n    *   *Re-evaluating Page 1:* Since there is no content, writing 300 words of analysis on a security check page is challenging but necessary to meet the prompt's requirement. I will focus on the methodological implication of inaccessible literature in this specific domain.\n    *   *Re-evaluating Page 2:* There is enough content to discuss the PP plasma treatment in depth, contrasting it with the missing DVS/PEI specifics.\n    *   *Re-evaluating Page 3:* Discuss the DVS chemistry but emphasize the biological vs. industrial adhesive context difference.\n\n    *   *JSON Escaping:* I must escape double quotes `\"` as `\\\"` and newlines as `\\n`.\n\n    *   *Let's draft the text mentally to estimate word count.*\n    *   Page 1 Draft: This page represents a significant access barrier within the literature review process for divinyl sulfone crosslinked polyethylenimine adhesive coatings. The content provided is solely a security verification checkpoint from ResearchGate, indicating that automated scraping or network activity triggered a defense mechanism. Consequently, no experimental evidence regarding plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide substrates could be extracted from this specific URL. The absence of data here highlights a common challenge in aggregating proprietary or hosted academic PDFs where full-text access is restricted behind authentication walls. For the research question concerning measured peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths, this source contributes zero quantitative values. The methodology described is non-existent beyond the network handshake. There are no contradictions to existing knowledge because no scientific claims are made. The confidence assessment for any finding related to the research question is effectively zero, classified as LOW, because the source failed to deliver the promised title content regarding plasma-induced surface modification. This failure necessitates reliance on alternative open-access repositories like PMC or publisher direct links to verify claims about polyethylenimine modifications. T