ONS NOT OTHERWISE PROVIDED FOR; APPLICATIONS OF MATERIALS NOT OTHERWISE PROVIDED FOR [ C09K ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) MATERIALS FOR MISCELLANEOUS APPLICATIONS, NOT PROVIDED FOR ELSEWHERE [ C09K2208/00 ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) Aspects relating to compositions of drilling or well treatment fluids [ C09K2208/26 ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) Gel breakers other than bacteria or enzymes View 5 more classifications Hide more classifications ### Landscapes [ Chemical & Material Sciences ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) [ Life Sciences & Earth Sciences ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) * * * Show more Show less ## US20060081369A1 United States Patent application publication [ ](https://patentimages.storage.googleapis.com/41/39/49/126c0e00940c47/US20060081369A1.pdf) [ ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) [ ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) Inventor [Robert Kriegel](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) Current Assignee The listed assignees may be inaccurate. Google has not performed a legal analysis and makes no representation or warranty as to the accuracy of the list. Halliburton Energy Services Inc * * * Worldwide applications 2004 [ US ](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) Application number: US10/969,631 Filing date: 2004-10-20 Legal status: Expired - Fee Related * * * Application US10/969,631 events A timeline of key events for this patent application, including priority claims, publications, legal status, reassignments, and litigation. Google has not performed a legal analysis and makes no representation as to the accuracy or completeness of the events listed. 2004-10-20 [Application filed by Halliburton Energy Services Inc](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) 2004-10-20 [Priority to US10/969,631](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) 2004-10-20 [Assigned to HALLIBURTON ENERGY SERVICES, INC.](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) ASSIGNMENT OF ASSIGNORS INTEREST (SEE DOCUMENT FOR DETAILS). Assignors: KRIEGEL, ROBERT M. 2006-04-20 [Publication of US20060081369A1](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) 2006-11-07 Application granted 2006-11-07 [Publication of US7131492B2](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en) 2024-10-20 Anticipated expiration Status Expired - Fee Related * * * Info [Patent citations (21)](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en#patentCitations) [Cited by (9)](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en#citedBy) [Legal events](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en#legalEvents) [Similar documents](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en#similarDocuments) [Priority and Related Applications](https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en#relatedApplications) External links [USPTO](https://appft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=/netahtml/PTO/srchnum.html&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PG01&s1=20060081369.PGNR.) [USPTO PatentCenter](https://patentcenter.uspto.gov/applications/10969631) [USPTO Assignment](https://assignment.uspto.gov/patent/index.html#/patent/search/resultFilter?searchInput=20060081369) [Espacenet](https://worldwide.espacenet.com/publicationDetails/biblio?CC=US&NR=2006081369A1&KC=A1&FT=D) [Global Dossier](https://globaldossier.uspto.gov/result/application/US/10969631/1) [Discuss](https://patents.stackexchange.com/questions/tagged/US20060081369) ### Description translated from BACKGROUND * [0001] The present invention relat\n\n--- PAGE: Synthesis of polyethylenimine modified Fe 3 O 4 nanoparticles with ... ---\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436\nCONTENT:\n(https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#screen-reader-main-content)(https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#screen-reader-main-title) [![Elsevier logo](https://www.sciencedirect.com/shared-assets/24/images/elsevier-non-solus-new-grey.svg)ScienceDirect](https://www.sciencedirect.com/) * [Journals & Books](https://www.sciencedirect.com/browse/journals-and-books) * * [](https://www.sciencedirect.com/search \"Search\") [](https://www.sciencedirect.com/user/login?targetURL=%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS0927775713009436&from=globalheader \"My account\") [](https://www.sciencedirect.com/user/institution/login?targetURL=%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS0927775713009436 \"Sign In\") * [Access through **your organization**](https://www.sciencedirect.com/user/institution/login?targetUrl=%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS0927775713009436) * [Purchase PDF](https://www.sciencedirect.com/getaccess/pii/S0927775713009436/purchase) Search ScienceDirect ## Article preview * [Abstract](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#preview-section-abstract) * [Introduction](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#preview-section-introduction) * [Section snippets](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#preview-section-snippets) * [References (36)](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#preview-section-references) * [Cited by (61)](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436#preview-section-cited-by) [![Elsevier](https://www.sciencedirect.com/us-east-1/prod/91e815c6826a7342dcdd5de2dc12c28888886be8/image/elsevier-non-solus.svg)](https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/colloids-and-surfaces-a-physicochemical-and-engineering-aspects \"Go to Colloids and Surfaces A: Physicochemical and Engineering Aspects on ScienceDirect\") ## [Colloids and Surfaces A: Physicochemical and Engineering Aspects](https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/colloids-and-surfaces-a-physicochemical-and-engineering-aspects \"Go to Colloids and Surfaces A: Physicochemical and Engineering Aspects on ScienceDirect\") [Volume 443](https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/colloids-and-surfaces-a-physicochemical-and-engineering-aspects/vol/443/suppl/C \"Go to table of contents for this volume/issue\"), 20 February 2014, Pages 552-559 [![Colloids and Surfaces A: Physicochemical and Engineering Aspects](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/1-s2.0-S0927775713X00226-cov150h.gif)](https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/colloids-and-surfaces-a-physicochemical-and-engineering-aspects/vol/443/suppl/C) # Synthesis of polyethylenimine modified Fe3O4 nanoparticles with immobilized Cu2+ for highly efficient proteins adsorption Author links open overlay panelTingting Xia a, [Yueping Guan a](https://www.sciencedirect.com/author/7202922030/yueping-guan)Mingzhu Yang a, Wubin Xiong a, Ning Wang b, Shen Zhao a, [Chen Guo b](https://www.sciencedirect.com/author/55115916600/chen-guo) Show more Add to Mendeley Share Cite [https://doi.org/10.1016/j.colsurfa.2013.12.026](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.colsurfa.2013.12.026 \"Persistent link using digital object identifier\")[Get rights and content](https://s100.copyright.com/AppDispatchServlet?publisherName=ELS&contentID=S0927775713009436&orderBeanReset=true) ## Highlights * • [PEI](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/polyethyleneimine) was modified on the Fe3O4 [nanoparticles](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/nanoparticle) using bifunctional [GA](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/glutaraldehyde) as an intermediate. * • The concentration of ![single bond](https://sdfestaticassets-us-east-1.sciencedirectassets.com/shared-assets/55/entities/sbnd.gif)NH2 on the [NPs](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/nanoparticle) increased from 0.2 mmol/g to 0.53 mmol/g. * • The Fe3O4–PEI–Cu2+ [NPs](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/nanoparticle) shows high adsorption capacity for BHb (6000 mg/g). ## Abstract We report the modification of amine-functioned Fe3O4 [nanoparticles](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemical-engineering/nanoparticle) (provided by the Laboratory of Bio-Medical Materials of University of Science and Technology Beijing) with polyethylenimine (PEI) using glutaraldehyde (GA) as a linker to increase the concentration of primary amine groups on the surface. The resultant Fe3O4–PEI NPs with immobilized iminodiacetic acid (IDA)–Cu2+ groups were applied to investigate the adsorption capacity and selectivity of model proteins: bovine hemoglobin (BHb) and bovine serum albumin (BSA). The Fe3O4–PEI NPs were characterized by transmission electron microscopy (TEM), vibrating sample magnetometer (VSM), particle analyzer, attenuated total reflection-Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (ATR–FTIR), ninhydrin colorimetry and thermogravimetric analysis (TGA). The results showed that the well dispersed Fe3O4–PEI NPs had an average size of 172.6 nm and were super-paramagnetic with saturation magnetization of 71.11 emu/g. The characteristic peaks of [PEI](https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/polyethyleneimine) appeared in the ATR–FTIR spectra of Fe3O4–PEI NPs. The study of zeta potential measurement presented that the isoelectric points of the Fe3O4–PEI NPs increased to 10.5. Ninhydrin colorimetry analysis of primary amine groups showed that the concentration of primary amine groups on the surface of Fe3O4–PEI NPs increased to 0.45 mmol/g and that of TGA is 0.53 mmol/g. These results showed that PEI had been successfully modified on the surface of amine-functioned Fe3O4 NPs and the concentration of primary amine groups was significantly increased. The analysis of protein adsorption indicated that the adsorption capacity of BHb was up to about 6000 mg/g and that of BSA was only about 2000 mg/g, which was about one third of that of BHb. The research on the selectivity of protein adsorption was conducted by HPLC. The result showed that the adsorption capacity of BHb was 2.5 times as high as that of BSA, which further proved Fe3O4–PEI–Cu2+ NPs shows specific adsorption for proteins. These properties suggested the potential of the Fe3O4–PEI–Cu2+ NPs as protein adsorbent. ## Graphical abstract ![](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/1-s2.0-S0927775713009436-fx1.jpg) 1. [Download: Download high-res image (135KB)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/1-s2.0-S0927775713009436-fx1_lrg.jpg \"Download high-res image \\(135KB\\)\") 2. [Download: Download full-size image](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/1-s2.0-S0927775713009436-fx1.jpg \"Download full-size image\") ## Introduction Recently, magnetic separation has attracted considerable attention for their increasing applications in biotechnology and biomedicine, especially in the separation of proteins due to ongoing need of purified proteins both in terms of diagnostics and therapeutics [1], [2], [3], [4], [5]. The basic principle of magnetic separation is simply to use magnetic particles modified with affinity ligands already utilized in chromatography [6] to be conjugated with proteins and isolated under the action of an external magnetic field. Fe3O4 particles are most widely used as magnetic supports and endow magnetic separations with advantages of speed, easy use and affordability [7]. Magnetic separation has obtained some achievements in protein purification [8], [9], [10], [11], [12]. However, defects of magnetic adsorbents limit this method to analytical or laboratory scales, such as macroporous magnetic particles with relatively large specific surface areas that have big diffusion resistance within the particles and are easier to be “plugged” with biological foulants in their applications [13], or nonporous magnetic particles without sufficient active specific affinity ligands to provide linkage sites for protein adsorption [14]. It seems that nonporous magnetic particles with big concentration of functional groups can adsorb proteins efficiently. Therefore, it is of great significance to select nano-sized nonporous magnetic particles as raw material to be modified with suitable polymer in order to obtain enough reactive functional groups on the surface. PEI is a water-soluble cationic polymer with high density of primary, secondary and tertiary amine functional groups in each polymer chain (Scheme 1). As an ideal candidate for grafting polymer, PEI has been successfully applied both in terms of biomedicine [15], [16], [17] and environmental remediation [18], [19]. The effectiveness of PEI in these applications should owe to its amine-rich structure, for instance, branched PEI (MW = 10,000 g/mol) has 81 primary amine groups per molecule. This amine-rich polymer will determine the surface charge and the number of available functional groups on the surface of the magnetic particles. Moreover, it is desired to enhance the dispersibility of magnetic particles by the electrostatic repulsive force and steric hindrance of the PEI [20]. It is also crucial to design an ideal ligand to guarantee the specific adsorption of target proteins by modified magnetic particles. Immobilized metal ions as pseudo affinity ligands have been of much interest since it was first introduced [21]. Such as Deniz Türkmen chelated Cu2+ on the PEI modified magnetic poly(2-hydroxyethylmethacrylate) (mPHEMA) beads to adsorb cytochrome c (cyt c) [22], Zheng Yeyou synthesized a novel IMAC material, zirconium-phosphate (Zr4+-PO3)-modified magnetic Fe3O4/GMA-co-EDMA (core/shell) (Zr4+-Fe3O4 @polymer) microspheres for the selective capture of phosphopeptides from protein tryptic digests[23] and so on. This kind immobilized metal affinity (IMA) separation is based on the interaction between chelated metal ions (Co2+, Zn2+, Ni2+ or Cu2+) and the thiol group cysteine, the indoyl group of tryptophan or especially the imidazole group of histidine of proteins [24]. Compared with classical bio-ligands, such as Protein A [25], metal ions have relatively low specificity, but they have higher physical and chemical stability, considerable bonding capacity and low cost, which is suitable for large-scale protein separation [26]. The iminodiacetic acid (IDA), the extensively used carboxymethylated amine, was selected as chelating ligand for Cu2+. There exists two carboxyl per molecular of IDA, which strengthens the binding force between Cu2+ and magnetic particles compared with directly using primary amine groups modified on the magnetic particles to bond Cu2+. Therefore, we selected nano-sized Fe3O4 particles as inorganic magnetic core to be modified with branched PEI using bifunctional agent: glutaradehyde (GA) as reactive intermediate. The properties of the Fe3O4–PEI nanoparticles (NPs) were characterized by transmission electron microscopy (TEM), vibrating sample magnetometer (VSM), attenuated total reflection-Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (ATR–FTIR), particle analyzer, ninhydrin colorimetry and thermogravimetric analysis (TGA). The synthesized Fe3O4–PEI NPs immobilized Cu2+ using iminodiacetic acid (IDA) groups as chelating ligands, yielding Fe3O4–PEI–Cu2+ NPs to investigate the adsorption capacity and selectivity for model proteins: BHb and BSA. ## Access through your organization Check access to the full text by signing in through your organization. [Access through **your organization**](https://www.sciencedirect.com/user/institution/login?targetUrl=%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS0927775713009436) ## Section snippets ## Materials Bare Fe3O4 NPs (without primary amino groups on the surface) and amine-functioned Fe3O4 NPs (the concentration of primary amine groups on the surface is 0.2 mmol/g and the size is 15 nm) were both provided by the Beijing GiGNano Biointerface Company. Glutaraldehyde (GA, 50% in water), sodium chloroacetate (CH2ClCOONa) were supplied by Tian Jin Zhi Yuan Reagent Co., Ltd. (TianJin). Ethylenediamine (EDA), glacial acetic acid (HAC), cupric sulphate (CuSO4·5H2O), sodium hydroxide (NaOH) and disodium ## Synthesis and characterization of PEI modified Fe3O4 magnetic nanoparticles Scheme 1 schematically shows the preparation process of PEI modified Fe3O4 magnetic nanoparticles. GA as the reactive intermediate modified amine-functioned Fe3O4 NPs with PEI through the reaction between aldehyde groups from GA and primary amino groups from amine-functioned Fe3O4 NPs and PEI respectively. The added EDA reacted with the aldehyde groups that have not bonded with PEI. Generated imines which contained C![double bond](https://sdfestaticassets-us-east-1.sciencedirectassets.com/shared-assets/55/entities/dbnd.gif)N were changed into more stable secondary amines by NaBH4. The added EDA and ## Conclusions Well-defined Fe3O4–PEI NPs were fabricated via a linker of GA. The magnetic particles with a mean size of 172.6 nm exhibited superparamagnetism and the high saturation magnetization (71.11 emu/g). Branched PEI facilitated improving the concentration of primary amine groups to 0.53 mmol/g, which provided more linkage sites on the surface of NPs. After chemical modification with IDA–Cu2+ groups to form magnetic adsorbents, the Fe3O4–PEI–Cu2+ NPs showed very high adsorption capacity for BHb (6000 ## Acknowledgments This work was financially supported by National Natural Science Foundation of China (51274035) and National Basic Research Program of China (2013CB632602). Recommended articles ## References (36) * Z.G. Peng _et al._ ### [ Adsorption and desorption of lysozyme on nano-sized magnetic particles and its conformational changes](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0927776504000918) ### Colloid Surf. B (2004) * X. Liu _et al._ ### [ Synthesis of amino-silane modified superparamagnetic silica supports and their use for protein immobilization](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0927775704001438) ### Colloid Surf. A (2004) * D. Shao _et al._ ### [ Effective adsorption and separation of lysozyme with PAA-modified Fe3O4@silica core/shell microspheres](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021979709004032) ### J. Colloid Interface Sci. (2009) * Z. Ma _et al._ ### [ Superparamagnetic silica nanoparticles with immobilized metal affinity ligands for protein adsorption](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304885305006992) ### J. Magn. Magn. Mater. (2006) * C. Chiang _et al._ ### [ Purification of transfection-grade plasmid DNA from bacterial cells with superparamagnetic nanoparticles](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304885305007122) ### J. Magn. Magn. Mater. (2006) * Y. Chen _et al._ ### [ Immobilization of polyethylenimine nanoclusters onto a cation exchange resin through self-cross\n\n\nFor each page, provide:\n1. A 300-400 word deep analysis focused on findings relevant to the research question, including:\n   - Key data points, statistics, and numerical findings\n   - Methodology or approach described (if any)\n   - Contradictions or tensions with commonly known information\n   - Confidence assessment for each key finding: HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW\n2. Which STORM perspectives are covered (from: Scientific, Regulatory, Industry, Economic, Public_Health, Historical, Regional, Methodological, Emerging_Trends)\n3. 3-5 specific facts with numbers, dates, or named entities\n4. Any data tables, statistics, or quantitative results (preserve exact numbers)\n5. What new understanding this page adds\n"}],"response_content":"{\n  \"research_notes\": [\n    {\n      \"page_url\": \"https://patents.google.com/patent/US20060081369A1/en\",\n      \"analysis\": \"This patent document describes divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinking agents, which directly addresses the chemical component of the research question. However, the application context is strictly subterranean treatment fluids for oil and gas wells, diverging significantly from the adhesive coating context on polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The abstract specifies viscosified treatment fluids comprising an aqueous base and a crosslinked gelling agent with at least one alkyl sulfone bridge. There is no mention of polyethylenimine (PEI), plasma activation, or mechanical adhesion testing such as peel or lap-shear strength. Consequently, this document provides no experimental evidence regarding DVS-crosslinked PEI adhesive coatings on the specified substrates. The methodology focuses on formation treatment rather than surface adhesion science. A key tension exists between the chemical utility of DVS confirmed here and the lack of data supporting its use in the specific adhesive architecture queried. The confidence in the finding that DVS is used as a crosslinker is HIGH, but the confidence in its relevance to the specific adhesion question is LOW. This source confirms DVS availability and classification under chemistry/metallurgy for adhesives generally (C09), but fails to provide the specific empirical data required to compare measured adhesion strengths with molecular dynamics predictions. It serves primarily to establish the existence of DVS crosslinking technology in industrial patents without validating the specific material system. The patent classifications indicate compositions containing cross-linking agents based on water or polar solvents. The legal status is Expired - Fee Related, suggesting the technology may not have been commercially sustained in this specific form. The filing date places this technology in a specific historical context, potentially predating recent advances in plasma activation techniques. The inventor and assignee indicate an industry focus on energy extraction rather than materials science for adhesion. This reinforces the conclusion that while DVS chemistry is established, the specific interface science regarding PEI on plasma-activated polymers or oxides is not covered. The absence of molecular dynamics or single-bond work of adhesion predictions is notable, highlighting a gap between patent literature on crosslinkers and computational materials science. Therefore, this document contributes negatively to the research question by defining the boundaries of existing DVS patent literature, showing it does not encompass the specific adhesive systems under investigation.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Industry\",\n        \"Methodological\",\n        \"Historical\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Patent US20060081369A1 was filed on 2004-10-20\",\n        \"Assignee is Halliburton Energy Services Inc\",\n        \"Inventor is Robert Kriegel\",\n        \"Legal status is Expired - Fee Related\",\n        \"Classification includes C09K8/685 for cross-linking agents\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_results\": [\n        \"Filing Date: 2004-10-20\",\n        \"Publication Date: 2006-04-20\",\n        \"Application Number: US10/969,631\"\n      ],\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Confirms DVS is a known crosslinker in industrial patents but reveals a lack of documented application in PEI adhesive coatings on plasma-activated substrates within this specific patent family.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"page_url\": \"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0927775713009436\",\n      \"analysis\": \"This article details the synthesis of polyethylenimine (PEI) modified Fe3O4 nanoparticles, addressing the polymer component of the research question but utilizing glutaraldehyde (GA) as the linker instead of divinyl sulfone (DVS). The methodology involves modifying amine-functioned nanoparticles to increase primary amine concentration, achieving 0.53 mmol/g as measured by thermogravimetric analysis. While this demonstrates successful PEI grafting, the substrate is magnetic iron oxide rather than plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The study focuses on protein adsorption capacity rather than mechanical adhesion strengths like peel or lap-shear. There is no comparison with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion. The use of GA suggests a different crosslinking mechanism than DVS, which may affect bond stability and density. Confidence in the quantitative data regarding amine concentration is HIGH, but relevance to the specific DVS/substrate adhesion question is LOW. The research highlights a methodological parallel where PEI is used to enhance surface functionality, yet it diverges in crosslinker chemistry and performance metrics. The absence of DVS prevents direct comparison of adhesion strengths. However, the detailed characterization techniques provide a benchmark for how PEI modifications are typically validated, which could inform experimental design for the DVS system. The publication date indicates relatively recent techniques in PEI modification, suggesting that while DVS-specific data is missing, PEI surface engineering is active. This page adds understanding of PEI grafting densities achievable with alternative crosslinkers, serving as a comparative baseline rather than direct evidence. The study reports a specific increase in primary amine groups from 0.2 mmol/g to 0.53 mmol/g, quantifying the efficiency of the PEI modification process. The nanoparticles exhibited superparamagnetism with saturation magnetization of 71.11 emu/g, indicating successful preservation of core properties during coating. The adsorption capacity difference between bovine hemoglobin and bovine serum albumin underscores the specificity achievable with PEI coatings, which might analogously relate to adhesive specificity on different substrates. However, the lack of mechanical testing data means no correlation can be drawn to peel strength. The reliance on wet chemistry characterization rather than interfacial mechanics limits the utility for adhesion modeling. The reference to immobilized metal affinity separation further distances the application from structural adhesives. This document confirms that PEI modification is viable for enhancing surface group density, a prerequisite for strong adhesion, but does not validate the DVS crosslinking route. The explicit use of GA instead of DVS marks a critical divergence. Thus, while it validates PEI surface engineering, it does not support the specific hypothesis regarding DVS crosslinked systems on plasma-activated substrates.\",\n      \"storm_perspectives\": [\n        \"Scientific\",\n        \"Methodological\",\n        \"Emerging_Trends\"\n      ],\n      \"specific_facts\": [\n        \"Published in Colloids and Surfaces A Volume 443 on 20 February 2014\",\n        \"Pages 552-559\",\n        \"Authors include Tingting Xia and Yueping Guan\",\n        \"Supported by National Natural Science Foundation of China (51274035)\",\n        \"Used glutaraldehyde (GA) as a linker instead of DVS\"\n      ],\n      \"quantitative_results\": [\n        \"Primary amine concentration increased to 0.53 mmol/g\",\n        \"Average nanoparticle size of 172.6 nm\",\n        \"Saturation magnetization of 71.11 emu/g\",\n        \"BHb adsorption capacity up to 6000 mg/g\",\n        \"BSA adsorption capacity about 2000 mg/g\"\n      ],\n      \"new_understanding\": \"Establishes that PEI surface modification can significantly increase amine density (0.2 to 0.53 mmol/g) using crosslinkers, but highlights that glutaraldehyde is the documented linker in this context, not DVS, and no mechanical adhesion data is provided.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}","response_reasoning":"Thinking Process:\n\n1.  **Analyze the Request:**\n    *   **Role:** Research analyst.\n    *   **Task:** Read 2 provided web pages and create a research note for each.\n    *   **Research Question:** What experimental evidence exists for divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinked polyethylenimine (PEI/BPEI) adhesive coatings on plasma-activated polypropylene and aluminum oxide substrates, and how do measured peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths compare with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion?\n    *   **Output Format:** Valid JSON only. No prose, no markdown, no code fences.\n    *   **Content Requirements per Page:**\n        1.  300-400 word deep analysis (findings, data, methodology, contradictions, confidence).\n        2.  STORM perspectives covered.\n        3.  3-5 specific facts (numbers, dates, entities).\n        4.  Data tables/statistics/quantitative results.\n        5.  New understanding added.\n    *   **Constraint:** MUST respond with valid JSON only.\n\n2.  **Analyze Page 1 (US20060081369A1 - Google Patents):**\n    *   **Content:** Patent abstract and classifications regarding \"Divinyl sulfone crosslinking agents and methods of use in subterranean applications\".\n    *   **Relevance to Research Question:** The title mentions \"Divinyl sulfone crosslinking agents\". However, the abstract specifies \"viscosified treatment fluids\" for \"subterranean formation\" (oil/gas wells). It does *not* mention PEI, adhesive coatings, polypropylene, aluminum oxide, plasma activation, peel strength, lap-shear, or molecular dynamics.\n    *   **Analysis:** This page is largely irrelevant to the specific research question regarding adhesive coatings on specific substrates (PP/Al2O3) and mechanical testing vs MD simulations. It confirms DVS is used as a crosslinker, but in a completely different context (downhole fluids).\n    *   **Word Count Challenge:** I need to write 300-400 words analyzing this. Since the content is irrelevant, I must analyze *why* it is irrelevant while extracting what little info exists about DVS crosslinking to satisfy the length constraint without hallucinating relevance. I need to be honest about the lack of evidence for the specific query.\n    *   **Facts:** Patent US20060081369A1, Filed 2004-10-20, Assignee Halliburton, Inventor Robert Kriegel.\n    *   **STORM Perspectives:** Industry (oil/gas), Methodological (crosslinking).\n\n3.  **Analyze Page 2 (ScienceDirect - Synthesis of polyethylenimine modified Fe3O4 nanoparticles...):**\n    *   **Content:** Article about PEI modified Fe3O4 nanoparticles using glutaraldehyde (GA) as a linker, not DVS. Used for protein adsorption (BHb, BSA).\n    *   **Relevance to Research Question:** Mentions PEI modification. However, the crosslinker is Glutaraldehyde (GA), not Divinyl Sulfone (DVS). The substrate is Fe3O4 nanoparticles, not plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The application is protein adsorption, not adhesive coatings/peel strength. No molecular dynamics mentioned.\n    *   **Analysis:** This page provides evidence of PEI modification using a crosslinker (GA), but explicitly *not* DVS. It highlights a methodological gap for the research question (DVS vs GA). It provides data on amine concentration and adsorption capacity, which might be analogous to coating density but doesn't answer the adhesion strength question.\n    *   **Word Count Challenge:** Need 300-400 words. I will detail the methodology used (GA vs DVS implication), the quantitative results (amine concentration, adsorption capacity), and explicitly state the lack of connection to the specific substrates/adhesion metrics in the research question.\n    *   **Facts:** Volume 443, 20 February 2014, Pages 552-559, Amine concentration 0.53 mmol/g, BHb adsorption 6000 mg/g.\n    *   **STORM Perspectives:** Scientific, Methodological, Emerging_Trends (nanoparticles).\n\n4.  **Drafting the Content (Mental Check on Word Counts):**\n    *   *Page 1 Analysis:* Must emphasize the mismatch. DVS is present, but context is wrong. No PEI, no adhesion data.\n    *   *Page 2 Analysis:* PEI is present, but crosslinker is GA. No adhesion data. Substrates differ.\n    *   *Constraint Check:* JSON only. No markdown inside the JSON strings (escape quotes).\n    *   *Word Count:* I need to ensure the analysis text for each page is between 300-400 words. This is tight for irrelevant content. I will expand on the methodological implications of the findings relative to the research question (e.g., \"While DVS is identified...\").\n\n    *Drafting Page 1 Analysis:*\n    This patent document describes divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinking agents, which directly addresses the chemical component of the research question. However, the application context is strictly subterranean treatment fluids for oil and gas wells, diverging significantly from the adhesive coating context on polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The abstract specifies viscosified treatment fluids comprising an aqueous base and a crosslinked gelling agent with at least one alkyl sulfone bridge. There is no mention of polyethylenimine (PEI), plasma activation, or mechanical adhesion testing such as peel or lap-shear strength. Consequently, this document provides no experimental evidence regarding DVS-crosslinked PEI adhesive coatings on the specified substrates. The methodology focuses on formation treatment rather than surface adhesion science. A key tension exists between the chemical utility of DVS confirmed here and the lack of data supporting its use in the specific adhesive architecture queried. The confidence in the finding that DVS is used as a crosslinker is HIGH, but the confidence in its relevance to the specific adhesion question is LOW. This source confirms DVS availability and classification under chemistry/metallurgy for adhesives generally (C09), but fails to provide the specific empirical data required to compare measured adhesion strengths with molecular dynamics predictions. It serves primarily to establish the existence of DVS crosslinking technology in industrial patents without validating the specific material system.\n\n    *Count Check:* ~180 words. I need to expand. I will elaborate on the classifications and legal status to fill space while remaining analytical.\n    *Expansion:* The patent classifications (C09K8/685) indicate compositions containing cross-linking agents based on water or polar solvents. The legal status is Expired - Fee Related, suggesting the technology may not have been commercially sustained in this specific form. The filing date of 2004-10-20 places this technology in a specific historical context, potentially predating recent advances in plasma activation techniques. The inventor, Robert Kriegel, and assignee, Halliburton Energy Services Inc, indicate an industry focus on energy extraction rather than materials science for adhesion. This reinforces the conclusion that while DVS chemistry is established, the specific interface science regarding PEI on plasma-activated polymers or oxides is not covered. The absence of molecular dynamics or single-bond work of adhesion predictions is notable, highlighting a gap between patent literature on crosslinkers and computational materials science. Therefore, this document contributes negatively to the research question by defining the boundaries of existing DVS patent literature, showing it does not encompass the specific adhesive systems under investigation.\n\n    *Total Page 1 Analysis:* ~320 words.\n\n    *Drafting Page 2 Analysis:*\n    This article details the synthesis of polyethylenimine (PEI) modified Fe3O4 nanoparticles, addressing the polymer component of the research question but utilizing glutaraldehyde (GA) as the linker instead of divinyl sulfone (DVS). The methodology involves modifying amine-functioned nanoparticles to increase primary amine concentration, achieving 0.53 mmol/g as measured by thermogravimetric analysis. While this demonstrates successful PEI grafting, the substrate is magnetic iron oxide rather than plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The study focuses on protein adsorption capacity (6000 mg/g for bovine hemoglobin) rather than mechanical adhesion strengths like peel or lap-shear. There is no comparison with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion. The use of GA suggests a different crosslinking mechanism than DVS, which may affect bond stability and density. Confidence in the quantitative data regarding amine concentration is HIGH, but relevance to the specific DVS/substrate adhesion question is LOW. The research highlights a methodological parallel where PEI is used to enhance surface functionality, yet it diverges in crosslinker chemistry and performance metrics. The absence of DVS prevents direct comparison of adhesion strengths. However, the detailed characterization techniques (TEM, VSM, ATR-FTIR) provide a benchmark for how PEI modifications are typically validated, which could inform experimental design for the DVS system. The publication date of 2014 indicates relatively recent techniques in PEI modification, suggesting that while DVS-specific data is missing, PEI surface engineering is active. This page adds understanding of PEI grafting densities achievable with alternative crosslinkers, serving as a comparative baseline rather than direct evidence.\n\n    *Count Check:* ~220 words. Need to expand.\n    *Expansion:* The study reports a specific increase in primary amine groups from 0.2 mmol/g to 0.53 mmol/g, quantifying the efficiency of the PEI modification process. The nanoparticles exhibited superparamagnetism with saturation magnetization of 71.11 emu/g, indicating successful preservation of core properties during coating. The adsorption capacity difference between bovine hemoglobin and bovine serum albumin (2.5 times higher for BHb) underscores the specificity achievable with PEI coatings, which might analogously relate to adhesive specificity on different substrates. However, the lack of mechanical testing data means no correlation can be drawn to peel strength. The reliance on wet chemistry characterization rather than interfacial mechanics limits the utility for adhesion modeling. The reference to immobilized metal affinity separation further distances the application from structural adhesives. This document confirms that PEI modification is viable for enhancing surface group density, a prerequisite for strong adhesion, but does not validate the DVS crosslinking route. The explicit use of GA instead of DVS marks a critical divergence. Thus, while it validates PEI surface engineering, it does not support the specific hypothesis regarding DVS crosslinked systems on plasma-activated substrates.\n\n    *Total Page 2 Analysis:* ~350 words.\n\n5.  **JSON Structure:**\n    *   Root object.\n    *   Key: \"research_notes\" (array of objects).\n    *   Each object: \"page_url\", \"analysis\", \"storm_perspectives\", \"specific_facts\", \"quantitative_results\", \"new_understanding\".\n    *   Ensure all strings are escaped properly (no newlines unless escaped, no unescaped quotes).\n    *   Ensure word counts are met.\n\n6.  **Final Review against Constraints:**\n    *   Valid JSON only.\n    *   No markdown fences.\n    *   No prose outside JSON.\n    *   Word count 300-400 for analysis sections.\n    *   Specific facts (3-5).\n    *   STORM perspectives list.\n\n    *Self-Correction on Word Count:* I need to be very careful to hit the 300-400 range. I will count carefully.\n    *Page 1 Draft:*\n    This patent document describes divinyl sulfone (DVS) crosslinking agents, which directly addresses the chemical component of the research question. However, the application context is strictly subterranean treatment fluids for oil and gas wells, diverging significantly from the adhesive coating context on polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The abstract specifies viscosified treatment fluids comprising an aqueous base and a crosslinked gelling agent with at least one alkyl sulfone bridge. There is no mention of polyethylenimine (PEI), plasma activation, or mechanical adhesion testing such as peel or lap-shear strength. Consequently, this document provides no experimental evidence regarding DVS-crosslinked PEI adhesive coatings on the specified substrates. The methodology focuses on formation treatment rather than surface adhesion science. A key tension exists between the chemical utility of DVS confirmed here and the lack of data supporting its use in the specific adhesive architecture queried. The confidence in the finding that DVS is used as a crosslinker is HIGH, but the confidence in its relevance to the specific adhesion question is LOW. This source confirms DVS availability and classification under chemistry/metallurgy for adhesives generally (C09), but fails to provide the specific empirical data required to compare measured adhesion strengths with molecular dynamics predictions. It serves primarily to establish the existence of DVS crosslinking technology in industrial patents without validating the specific material system. The patent classifications indicate compositions containing cross-linking agents based on water or polar solvents. The legal status is Expired - Fee Related, suggesting the technology may not have been commercially sustained in this specific form. The filing date places this technology in a specific historical context, potentially predating recent advances in plasma activation techniques. The inventor and assignee indicate an industry focus on energy extraction rather than materials science for adhesion. This reinforces the conclusion that while DVS chemistry is established, the specific interface science regarding PEI on plasma-activated polymers or oxides is not covered. The absence of molecular dynamics or single-bond work of adhesion predictions is notable, highlighting a gap between patent literature on crosslinkers and computational materials science. Therefore, this document contributes negatively to the research question by defining the boundaries of existing DVS patent literature, showing it does not encompass the specific adhesive systems under investigation. \n    *Page 2 Draft:*\n    This article details the synthesis of polyethylenimine (PEI) modified Fe3O4 nanoparticles, addressing the polymer component of the research question but utilizing glutaraldehyde (GA) as the linker instead of divinyl sulfone (DVS). The methodology involves modifying amine-functioned nanoparticles to increase primary amine concentration, achieving 0.53 mmol/g as measured by thermogravimetric analysis. While this demonstrates successful PEI grafting, the substrate is magnetic iron oxide rather than plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The study focuses on protein adsorption capacity rather than mechanical adhesion strengths like peel or lap-shear. There is no comparison with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion. The use of GA suggests a different crosslinking mechanism than DVS, which may affect bond stability and density. Confidence in the quantitative data regarding amine concentration is HIGH, but relevance to the specific DVS/substrate adhesion question is LOW. The research highlights a methodological parallel where PEI is used to enhance surface functionality, yet it diverges in crosslinker chemistry and performance metrics. The absence of DVS prevents direct comparison of adhesion strengths. However, the detailed characterization techniques provide a benchmark for how PEI modifications are typically validated, which could inform experimental design for the DVS system. The publication date indicates relatively recent techniques in PEI modification, suggesting that while DVS-specific data is missing, PEI surface engineering is active. This page adds understanding of PEI grafting densities achievable with alternative crosslinkers, serving as a comparative baseline rather than direct evidence. The study reports a specific increase in primary amine groups from 0.2 mmol/g to 0.53 mmol/g, quantifying the efficiency of the PEI modification process. The nanoparticles exhibited superparamagnetism with saturation magnetization of 71.11 emu/g, indicating successful preservation of core properties during coating. The adsorption capacity difference between bovine hemoglobin and bovine serum albumin underscores the specificity achievable with PEI coatings, which might analogously relate to adhesive specificity on different substrates. However, the lack of mechanical testing data means no correlation can be drawn to peel strength. The reliance on wet chemistry characterization rather than interfacial mechanics limits the utility for adhesion modeling. The reference to immobilized metal affinity separation further distances the application from structural adhesives. This document confirms that PEI modification is viable for enhancing surface group density, a prerequisite for strong adhesion, but does not validate the DVS crosslinking route. The explicit use of GA instead of DVS marks a critical divergence. Thus, while it validates PEI surface engineering, it does not support the specific hypothesis regarding DVS crosslinked systems on plasma-activated substrates. \n    *Check:* Both look good. Now construct JSON. Escape newlines as \\n.\n\n    *Wait, one more check:* The prompt asks for \"300-400 word deep analysis\". I need to make sure I don't go under. I will count again.\n    Page 1: 346 words.\n    Page 2: 363 words.\n    Perfect.\n\n    *JSON Escaping:* I need to make sure quotes inside the text are escaped as \\\". Newlines as \\n.\n    *STORM Perspectives:* List of strings.\n    *Specific Facts:* List of strings.\n    *Quantitative Results:* List of strings (or object? Prompt says \"Any data tables...\". I will use a list of strings to be safe and consistent).\n    *New Understanding:* String.\n\n    *Final check on JSON validity:* No trailing commas. Proper bracket closing.\n\n    *Wait, one detail:* \"No prose, no markdown, no code fences — just the JSON object.\"\n    I must ensure the output starts immediately with `{`.\n\n    *Let's assemble.*\n","input_tokens":9460,"output_tokens":5585,"reasoning_tokens":3886,"duration_ms":69908.2991000032,"cost_usd":0.011172},{"ts":"2026-03-12T02:16:07.799735+00:00","vid":"WEB_20260312T015506_435334","node":"structured","type":"llm_detail","call_type"